# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: amazon-rainforest
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The **2019 Amazon rainforest wildfires** season saw a year-to-year surge in fires occurring in the Amazon rainforest and Amazon biome within Brazil, Bolivia, Paraguay, and Peru during that year's Amazonian tropical dry season.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Fires normally occur around the dry season as slash-and-burn methods are used to clear the forest to make way for agriculture, livestock, logging, and mining, leading to deforestation of the Amazon rainforest.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Such activity is generally illegal within these nations, but enforcement of environmental protection can be lax.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The increased rates of fire counts in 2019 led to international concern about the fate of the Amazon rainforest, which is the world's largest terrestrial carbon dioxide sink and plays a significant role in mitigating global warming.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] As of August 29, 2019, INPE reported more than 80,000 fires across all of Brazil, a 77% year-to-year increase for the same tracking period, with more than 40,000 in the Brazil's Legal Amazon (*Amazônia Legal* or BLA), which contains 60% of the Amazon.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Similar year-to-year increases in fires were subsequently reported in Bolivia, Paraguay and Peru, with the 2019 fire counts within each nation of over 19,000, 11,000 and 6,700, respectively, as of August 29, 2019.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] It is estimated that over 906 thousand hectares (2.24×10^6 acres; 9,060 km2; 3,500 mi2) of forest within the Amazon biome has been lost to fires in 2019.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In addition to the impact on global climate, the fires created environmental concerns from the excess carbon dioxide (CO2) and carbon monoxide (CO) within the fires' emissions, potential impacts on the biodiversity of the Amazon, and threats to indigenous tribes that live within the forest.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Ecologists estimated that the dieback from the Amazon rainforest due to the fires could cost Brazil US$957 billion to US$3.5 trillion over a 30-year period.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro initially remained ambivalent and rejected international calls to take action, asserting that the criticism was sensationalist.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Following increased pressure at the 45th G7 summit and a threat to reject the pending European Union–Mercosur free trade agreement, Bolsonaro dispatched over 44,000 Brazilian troops and allocated funds to fight the fires, and later signed a decree to prevent such fires for a sixty-day period.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Other Amazonian countries have been affected by the wildfires in higher or lesser degree.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The number of hectares of Bolivian rainforest affected by the wildfires were roughly equal to those of Brazil, being the area of Bolivia only about one-eighth of Brazil's.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolivian president Evo Morales was similarly blamed for past policies that encouraged deforestation, Morales has also taken proactive measures to fight the fires and seek aid from other countries.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] At the G7 summit, Macron negotiated with the other nations to allocate US$22 million for emergency aid to the Amazonian countries affected by the fires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] There are 670 million ha (1.7 billion acres; 6.7 million km2; 2.6 million mi2) of Amazon rainforest.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Human-driven deforestation of the Amazon rainforest has been a major concern for decades as the rainforest's impact on the global climate has been measured.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] From a global climate perspective, the Amazon has been the world's largest carbon dioxide sink, and estimated to capture up to 25% of global carbon dioxide generation into plants and other biomass.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Without this sink, atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations would increase and contribute towards higher global temperatures, thus making the viability of the Amazon a global concern.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Further, when the forest is lost through fire, additional carbon dioxide is released to the atmosphere, and could potentially contribute significantly to the total carbon dioxide content.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The flora also generates significant quantities of water vapor through transpiration which travel large distances to other parts of South America via atmospheric rivers and contribute to the precipitation in these areas.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Human-driven deforestation of the Amazon is used to clear land for agriculture, livestock, and mining, and for its lumber.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Fires are most common in July through August.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In some cases, workers performing the burn are unskilled, and may inadvertently allow these fires to spread.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] While most countries in the Amazon do have laws and environmental enforcement against deforestation, these are not well enforced, and much of the slash-and-burn activity is done illegally.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Deforestation leads to a large number of observed fires across the Amazon during the dry season, usually tracked by satellite data.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] While it is possible for naturally occurring wildfires to occur in the Amazon, the chances are far less likely to occur, compared to those in California or in Australia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Even with global warming, spontaneous fires in the Amazon cannot come from warm weather alone, but warm weather is capable of exacerbating the fires once started as there will be drier biomass available for the fire to spread.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Alberto Setzer of INPE estimated that 99% of the wildfires in the Amazon basin are a result of human actions, either on purpose or accidentally.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Man-made fires in the Amazon also tend to elevate their smoke into the higher atmosphere due to the more intense burn of the dry biomass, compared with naturally occurring wildfires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Further evidence of the fires being caused by human activity is due to their clustering near roads and existing agricultural areas rather than remote parts of the forest.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On November 18, 2019, Brazilian authorities announced the official deforestation figures, based on the PRODES satellite monitoring system for the 2019 forest year—from August 1, 2018, to July 31, 2019.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The rate of deforestation was the "worst in more than a decade" with 970,000 hectares (2,400,000 acres) lost.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In August 2020 Brazil's National Institute for Space Research reported that satellite data shows that the number of fires in the Amazon increased by 28% to ~6,800 fires in July compared to the ~5,300 wildfires in July 2019.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] This indicated a, potentially worsened, repeat of 2019's accelerated destruction of one of the world's largest protectable buffers against global warming in 2020.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Amazon fires can be separated into three broad categories.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] First, deforestation-related fires are those used to prepare the area for agriculture after a primary forest being felled and the vegetation left to dry.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Second, there are those agricultural burns, when fires are used to clear existing pastureland and/or by smallholders and traditional people in rotational agriculture.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Finally, the previous fire types can escape beyond intended limits and invade standing forests.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] When a forest burns for the first time, fire intensity is usually low and flames are mostly restricted to the understory while repeated fire events have higher intensity.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Forest fires are a threat to the Amazonian biodiversity and jeopardize the ability of forest trees to mitigate climate change by storing carbon.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] When studying Amazonian fires, it is important to consider the marked spatial differences in precipitation patterns across the Amazon Basin, which does not have a single dry season.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Brazil's role in deforestation of the Amazon rainforest has been a significant issue during the 1930s, as 60% of the Amazon is contained within Brazil, designated as the Brazil's Legal Amazon (*Amazônia Legal*, BLA).
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Since the 1970s, Brazil has consumed approximately 12 percent of the forest, representing roughly 77.7 million ha (192 million acres)—an area larger than that of the US state of Texas.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Most of the deforestation has been for natural resources for the logging industry and land clearing for agricultural and mining use.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Forest removal to make way for cattle ranching was the leading cause of deforestation in the Brazilian Amazon from the mid-1960s on.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Amazon region has become the largest cattle ranching territory in the world.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] According to the World Bank, some 80% of deforested land is used for cattle ranching.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Seventy percent of formerly forested land in the Amazon, and 91% of land deforested since 1970, is used for livestock pasture.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Deforestation within Brazil is partially driven by growing demand for beef and soy exports, particularly to China and Hong Kong.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In the first seven months of 2019, soy exports to China rose by 18% due to trading tensions between the United States and China.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Brazil is one of the largest exporters of beef, accounting for more than 20% of global trade of the commodity.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Brazil exported over 1.6 million tonnes of beef in 2018, the highest volume in recorded history.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Brazil's cattle herd has increased by 56% over the last two decades.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Ranchers wait until the dry season to slash-and-burn to give time for the cattle to graze.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Soybean production has increased from 75.32 million metric tons in 2010/11 to 118.8 million metric tons in 2018/19.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Amazon accounts for 14 million of the 284 million acres of soy plantations in Brazil.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] While slash-and-burn can be controlled, unskilled farmers may end up causing wildfires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Wildfires have increased as the agricultural sector has pushed into the Amazon basin and spurred deforestation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In recent years, "land-grabbers" (*grileiros*) have been illegally cutting deep into the forest in "Brazil's indigenous territories and other protected forests throughout the Amazon".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Past data from INPE has shown the number of fires with the BLA from January to August in any year to be routinely higher than 60,000 fires from 2002 to 2007 and as high as 90,000 in 2003.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Fire counts have generally been higher in years of drought (2007 and 2010), which are often coupled with El Niño events.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Within international attention on the protection of the Amazon around the early 2000s, Brazil took a more proactive approach to deforestation of the Amazon rainforest.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Brazil also invested in more effective measures to fight fires, including fire-fighting airplanes in 2012.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By 2014, USAID was teaching the indigenous people how to fight fires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] As a result of enforcement of PPCDAM, the rate of deforestation in the Brazilian Amazon dropped 83.5% of their 2004 rates by 2012.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] However, in 2014, Brazil fell into an economic crisis, and as part of that recovery, pushed heavily on its exports of beef and soy to help bolster its economy, which caused a reversal in the falling deforestation rates.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Brazilian government has been defunding scientific research since the economic crisis.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] To support PPCDAM, the INPE began developing systems to monitor the Amazon rainforest.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] One early effort was the Amazon Deforestation Satellite Monitoring Project (PRODES), which is a highly detailed satellite imagery-based approach to calculate wildfires and deforestation losses on an annual basis.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In 2015, INPE launched five complementary projects as part of the Terra Brasilis project to monitor deforestation closer to real-time.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Among these include the Real-Time Deforestation Detection System (DETER) satellite alert system, allowing them to capture incidents of wildfires in 15-day cycles.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The daily data is published on the regularly updated Brazilian Environmental Institute government website, and later corroborated with the annual and more accurate PRODES data.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By December 2017, INPE had completed a modernization process and had expanded its system to analyze and share data on forest fires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] It launched its new TerraMA2Q platform—software which adapts fire-monitoring data software including the "occurrence of irregular fires".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Although the INPE was able to provide regional fire data since 1998, the modernization increased access.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Agencies that monitor and fight fires include the Brazilian Federal Environment and Renewable Resources Agency (IBAMA), as well as state authorities.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The INPE receives its images daily from 10 foreign satellites, including the Terra and Aqua satellites—part of the NASA's Earth Observation System (EOS).
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Land-grabbers had used Bolsonaro's election to extend their activities into cutting in the land of the previously isolated Apurinã people in Amazonas where the "world's largest standing tracts of unbroken rainforest" are found.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Upon entering office, Bolsonaro cut US$23 million from Brazil's environmental enforcement agency, making it difficult for the agency to regulate deforestation efforts.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] INPE alerted the Brazilian government to larger-than-normal growth in the number of fires through June to August 2019.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The first four months of the year were wetter-than-average, discouraging slash-and-burn efforts.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] However, with the start of the dry season in May 2019, the number of wildfires jumped greatly.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Additionally, NOAA reported that, regionally, the temperatures in the January–July 2019 period were the second warmest year-to-date on record.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] INPE reported a year-to-year increase of 88% in wildfire occurrences in June 2019.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] There was further increase in the rate of deforestation in July 2019, with the INPE estimating that more than 1,345 square kilometres (519 mi2; 134,500 ha; 332,000 acres) of land had been deforested in the month and would be on track to surpass the area of Greater London by the end of the month.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The month of August 2019 saw a large growth in the number of observed wildfires according to INPE.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 11, Amazonas had declared a state of emergency.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The state of Acre entered into an environmental alert on August 16.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In early August, local farmers in the Amazonian state of Pará placed an ad in the local newspaper calling for a *queimada* or "Day of Fire" on August 10, 2019, organizing large scale slash-and-burn operations knowing that there was little chance of interference from the government.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Shortly after, there was an increase in the number of wildfires in the region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] INPE reported on August 20 that it had detected 39,194 fires in the Amazon rainforest since January.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] This represented a 77 percent increase in the number of fires from the same time period in 2018.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] However, the NASA-funded NGO Global Fire Emissions Database (GFED) shows 2018 as an unusually low fire year compared to historic data from 2004 to 2005 which are years showing nearly double the number of counted fires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] INPE had reported that at least 74,155 fires have been detected in all of Brazil, which represents an 84-percent increase from the same period in 2018.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] NASA originally reported in mid-August that MODIS satellites reported average numbers of fires in the region compared with data from the past 15 years; the numbers were above average for the year in the states of Amazonas and Rondônia, but below average for Mato Grosso and Pará.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] NASA later clarified that the data set they had evaluated previous was through August 16, 2019.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 26, 2019, NASA included more recent MODIS imagery to confirm that the number of fires were higher than in previous years.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 29, 80,000 fires had broken out in Brazil which represents a 77% rise on the same period in 2018, according to BBC.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] While INPE's data had been reported in international sources earlier, news of the wildfires were not a major news story until around August 20, 2019.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On that day, the smoke plume from the fires in Rondônia and Amazonas caused the sky to darken at around 2 p.m. over São Paulo—which is almost 2,800 kilometres (1,700 miles) away from the Amazon basin on the eastern coast.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] NASA and US National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) also published satellite imagery from the Moderate Resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer (MODIS) on NASA's Terra satellite in alignment with INPE's own, that showed smoke plumes from the wildfires were visible from space.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] INPE and NASA data, along with photographs of the ongoing fires and impacts, caught international attention and became a rising topic on social media, with several world leaders, celebrities, and athletes expressing their concerns.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] According to *Vox*, of all the concurrent wildfires elsewhere in the world, the wildfires in the Amazon rainforest in Brazil were the most "alarming".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In the months prior to August 2019, Bolsonaro mocked international and environmental groups that felt his pro-business actions enabled deforestation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] At one point in August 2019, Bolsonaro jokingly calling himself "Captain Chainsaw" while asserting that INPE's data was inaccurate.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] After INPE announced an 88% increase of wildfires in July 2019, Bolsonaro claimed "the numbers were fake" and fired Ricardo Magnus Osório Galvão, the INPE director.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro claimed Galvão was using the data to lead an "anti-Brazil campaign".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro had claimed that the fires had been deliberately started by environmental NGOs, although he provided no evidence to back up the accusation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] NGOs such as WWF Brasil, Greenpeace, and the Brazilian Institute for Environmental Protection countered Bolsonaro's claims.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro, on August 22, argued that Brazil did not have the resources to fight the fires, as the "Amazon is bigger than Europe, how will you fight criminal fires in such an area?".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Historically, Brazil has been guarded about international intervention into the BLA, as the country sees the forest as a critical part of Brazil's economy.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro and his government have continued to speak out against any international oversight of the situation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro considered French President Emmanuel Macron's comments to have a "sensationalist tone" and accusing him of interfering in what he considers is a local problem.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Of Macron and German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Bolsonaro stated: "They still haven't realized that Brazil is under new direction.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro's foreign minister Ernesto Araújo has also condemned the international criticism of Bolsonaro's reaction to the wildfires, calling it "savage and unfair" treatment towards Bolsonaro and Brazil.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Araújo stated that: "President Bolsonaro's government is rebuilding Brazil", and that foreign nations were using the "environmental crisis" as a weapon to stop this rebuilding.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] General Eduardo Villas Bôas, former commander of the Brazilian Army, considered the criticism of world leaders, like Macron and Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau, to be directly challenging "Brazilian sovereignty", and may need to be met with military response.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] With increased pressure from the international community, Bolsonaro appeared more willing to take proactive steps against the fires, saying by August 23, 2019, that his government would take a "zero tolerance" approach to environmental crimes.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] He engaged the Brazilian military to help fight the wildfires on August 24, which Joint Staff member Lt.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Raul Botelho stated was to create a "positive perception" of the government's efforts.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Among military support included 43,000 troops as well as four firefighting aircraft, and an allocated US$15.7 million for fire-fighting operations.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Initial efforts were principally located in the state of Rondônia, but the Defense Ministry stated they plan to offer support for all seven states affected by the fires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On August 28, Bolsonaro signed a decree banning the setting of fires in Brazil for a period of 60 days, making exceptions for those fires made purposely to maintain environmental forest health, to combat wildfires, and by the indigenous people of Brazil.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] However, as most fires are set illegally, it is unclear what impact this decree could have.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Rodrigo Maia, president of the Chamber of Deputies, announced that he would form a parliatary committee to monitor the problem.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In addition, he said that the Chamber will hold a general commission in the following days to assess the situation and propose solutions to the government.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] After a report from Globo Rural reveal that a WhatsApp group of 70 people was involved with the *Day of Fire*, Jair Bolsonaro determined the opening of investigations by Federal Police.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In a webcast issued November 28, 2019, President Jair Bolsonaro blamed actor and environmentalist Leonardo DiCaprio for the rainforest wildfires, alleging NGOs set the fires in return for donations.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] DiCaprio, Global Wildlife Conservation, and IUCN Species Survival Commission condemn Bolsonaro's accusations.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Brazil banned clearing land by setting fire to it on 29 August 2019.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In regards to the displacement of the indigenous people, Amnesty International has highlighted the change in protection of lands belonging to the indigenous people, and have called on other nations to pressure Brazil to restore these rights, as they are also essential to protecting the rainforest.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Ivaneide Bandeira Cardoso, founder of Kanindé, a Porto Velho-based advocacy group for indigenous communities, said Bolsonaro is directly responsible for the escalation of forest fires throughout the Amazon this year.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Cardoso said the wildfires are a "tragedy that affects all of humanity" since the Amazon plays an important role in the global ecosystem as a carbon sink to reduce the effects of climate change.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Thousands of Brazilian citizens held protests in several major cities from August 24, 2019, onward to challenge the government's reaction to the wildfires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Protesters around the world also held events at Brazilian embassies, including in London, Paris, Mexico City, and Geneva.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In addition to environmental harm, the slash-and-burn actions leading to the wildfires have threatened the approximately 306,000 indigenous people in Brazil who reside near or within the rainforest.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro had spoken out against the need to respect the demarcation of lands for indigenous people established in the 1988 Constitution of Brazil.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Additionally, some indigenous groups that have traditionally used fire management practices for agricultural livelihoods are being criminalized.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Some of these tribes have vowed to fight back against those engaged in deforestation to protect their lands.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Kerexu Yxapyry, a leader from Santa Catarina's Kerexu tribe, describes this conflict as, "We know our struggle will be arduous.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Maybe many of our leaders will be killed, but we are organized.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] International leaders and environmental NGOs have condemned President Bolsonaro for the extent of the wildfires within the Brazilian portion of the Amazon.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Several international governments and environmental groups raised concerns at Bolsonaro's stance on the rainforest and the lack of attempts by his government to slow the wildfires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Among the most vocal was Macron, given the proximity of French Guiana to Brazil.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Macron called the Amazon wildfires an "international crisis", while claiming the rainforest produces "20% of the world's oxygen"—a statement disputed by academics.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Discussion about the fires came into the final negotiations of the EU–Mercosur Free Trade Agreement between the EU and Mercosur, a trade bloc of Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay, and Paraguay.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] With the wildfires on-going, both Macron and Irish Prime Minister Leo Varadkar have stated they will refuse to ratify the trade deal unless Brazil commits to protecting the environment.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] However, they have both been accused of using the fires as a pretext to scuttle an agreement that they already opposed on protectionist grounds.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Finance minister of Finland Mika Lintilä suggested the idea of an EU ban on Brazilian beef imports until the country takes steps to stop the deforestation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Secretary-General of the Rainforest Foundation Norway (RFN), Øyvind Eggen, said that neither the "official deforestation figures" published by Brazilian authorities on November 18, 2019, nor the number of wildfires in Amazon in 2019, were normal.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On September 10, 2019, the US House Foreign Affairs Committee held a hearing in Washington, DC entitled "Preserving the Amazon: A Shared Moral Imperative".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In Bolivia, *chaqueo* is an annual seasonal agricultural practice and commonly relies on the controlled use of fire.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] It was first authorized in 2001 during the government of Hugo Banzer Suarez.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolivia has 7.7 percent of the Amazon rainforest within its borders.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Bolivian Amazon covers 19.402 million hectares (47.94 million acres) which comprise 37.7 percent of Bolivia's forests and 17.7 percent of Bolivia's land mass.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolivia's forests cover a total of 51.407 million hectares (127.03 million acres), including the Chiquitano dry forests which is part of the Amazon biome and a transition zone between the Amazon rainforest and the drier forests of the southern Chaco region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By September 14, 2019, Bolivia—which is one-eighth the size of Brazil—lost nearly 6 million acres (2.4 million hectares) of "forest and savanna".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The fires destroyed about the same area of rainforest than in Brazil.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 16, Bolivia's Santa Cruz had declared a departmental emergency because of the forest fires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] From August 18 to August 23, approximately 800 thousand hectares (2.0 million acres) of the Chiquitano dry forests were destroyed, more than what was lost over a typical two-year period.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 24, the fires had already affected 1,011 thousand hectares (2.50 million acres) of forestland in the Santa Cruz and were burning near Santa Cruz, Bolivia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 26, wildfires had reached over 728 thousand hectares (1.80 million acres) of Bolivia's savanna and tropical forests, according to the Bolivian Information Agency (BIA).
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Over a period of five days, from August 18 to August 22, 450 thousand hectares (1.1 million acres) of forest near Roboré were burned.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On August 25, 4,000 state employees and volunteers were fighting the fires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Throughout August, wildfires have been spreading across four states. [By August 26, fires in the Dionisio Foianini Triangle—the Brazil-Bolivia-Paraguay triangle had reached savannah and tropical forest "near Bolivia's border with Paraguay and Brazil".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Bolivian government intervened after it was clear that the fires had surpassed local and regional response capabilities.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In the week of August 18, Morales dispatched soldiers and three helicopters to fight fires in an area about the size of Oregon.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On August 22, Morales contracted the Colorado-based Boeing 747 Supertanker (also known as Global SuperTanker) to conduct firefighting missions over the Bolivian Amazon.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The 747 Supertanker is the largest firefighting aircraft in the world, which can hold approximately 19,000 gallons of water per trip.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Morales has stated that the governments of many countries including Spain, Chile, Perú, France, the EU, among others have reached out to him to provide help for fighting the fires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The government had been trying to determine the cause of the fires, with the Bolivian land management authority attributing 87% of the fires present in areas without authorization.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Multiple NGOs assert that deforestation rates in Bolivia increased 200 percent after the government quadrupled available land for deforestation to small farmers in 2015.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Political opponents of Morales alleged that the Supreme Decree 3973 Archived August 25, 2019, at the Wayback Machine, a mandate to further beef production in the Amazon region, is a major cause of the Bolivian fires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] However, this Supreme Decree only extends the authorized but regulated use of fire already legal in Santa Cruz to the Beni Department, where forest fire issues are not a significant issue.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By September 9, total forests that had been affected by fires in Bolivia was estimated as 1,700 thousand hectares (4.2 million acres), more than double from estimates two weeks prior, but far less extended than the forest fires that occurred in 2004 and 2010.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 22, fire emergencies in Paraguay's Alto Paraguay district and the UNESCO protected Pantanal region were issued by its federal government.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Paraguay President Mario Abdo Benítez was in close contact with Bolivia's Morales to coordinate response efforts.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 17, as wind direction changed, flames from fires in Bolivia began to enter northern Paraguay's Three Giants natural reserve in the Paraguayan Pantanal natural region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 24, when the situation had stabilized, Paraguay had lost 39,000 hectares (96,000 acres) in the Pantanal.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] An Universidad Nacional de Asunción representative lamented the disaster failed to attract as much media attention as the fires in the Amazon rainforest.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] While most of the Pantanal regions—140,000 and 195,000 square kilometres (54,000 and 75,000 sq mi)—is within Brazil's borders in the state of Mato Grosso do Sul, the natural region also extends into Mato Grosso and portions of Bolivia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] It sprawls over an area estimated at between 140,000 and 195,000 square kilometres (54,000 and 75,000 sq mi).
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Within the Pantanal natural region, which is located between Brazil and Bolivia, is the "world's largest tropical wetland area".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] According one of the engineers charged with monitoring satellite data showing the "evolution of the fires", the Pantanal is a "complex, fragile, and high-risk ecosystem because it's being transformed from a wetland to a productive system".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Pantana is bounded by the Humid Chaco to the south, the Arid Chaco dry forests to the southwest, Cerrado savannas lie to the north, east and southeast, and the Chiquitano dry forests, to the west and northwest, where thousands of hectares burned in Bolivia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] A national parks researcher said that outsiders only know the Amazon, which is a "shame because the Pantanal is a very important ecological place".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Paraná River, which flows through Argentina, Brazil and Paraguay, is the "second largest river system in South America".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Peru had nearly twice the growth in the number of fires in 2019 than Brazil, with most believed to be illegally set by ranchers, miners, and coca growers.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Much of the fires are in the Madre de Dios which borders Brazil and Bolivia, though the fires there are not a result of those started in the other countries, according to the regional authority.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] However, they are still concerned about the impact of downwind emissions, particularly carbon monoxide, on residents of Madre de Dios.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] There were 128 forest fires reported in Peru in August 2019.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] By August 22, NASA's AIRS published maps of increased carbon monoxide and carbon dioxide resulting from Brazil's wildfires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On the same day, the European Union's Copernicus Climate Change Service reported a "discernible spike" in emissions of carbon monoxide and carbon dioxide generated by the fires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Areas downwind of the fires have become covered with smoke, which can potentially last upwards of months at a time if the fires are left to burn out.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Hospitals in cities like Porto Velho had reported over three times the average number of cases of patients affected by smoke over the same year-to-year period in August 2019 than in other previous years.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Besides hindering breathing, the smoke can exacerbates patients with asthma or bronchitis and have potential cancer risk, generally affecting the youth and elderly the most.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] According to the World Wildlife Fund, the jaguar, for example, is already "near threatened" and the loss of food supplies and habitat due to the fires make the situation more critical.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Scientists at the Natural History Museum in London described how while some forests have adapted to fire as "important part of a forest ecosystem's natural cycle", the Amazon rainforest—which is "made up of lowland, wetland forests"—is "not well-equipped to deal with fire".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Other Amazon basin ecosystems, like the Cerrado region, with its "large savannah, and lots of plants there have thick, corky, fire-resistant stems", is "fire-adapted".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Mazeika Sullivan, associate professor at Ohio State University's School of Environment and Natural Resources, explained that the fires could have a massive toll on wildlife in the short term as many animals in the Amazon are not adapted for extraordinary fires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Sloths, lizards, anteaters, and frogs may unfortunately perish in larger numbers than others due to their small size and lack of mobility.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Endemic species, like Milton's titi and Mura's saddleback tamarin, are believed to be beset by the fires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Aquatic species could also be affected due to the fires changing the water chemistry into a state unsuitable for life.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Long-term effects could be more catastrophic.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Parts of the Amazon rainforest's dense canopy were destroyed by the fires, therefore, exposing the lower levels of the ecosystem, which then alters the energy flow of the food chain.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The fires affect water chemistry (such as decreasing the amount of dissolved oxygen in the water), temperature, and erosion rates, which in turn affects fish and mammals that depend on fish, such as the giant otter.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On August 22, the Bishops Conference for Latin America called the fires a "tragedy" and urged the UN, the international community, and governments of Amazonian countries, to "take serious measures to save the world's lungs".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Colombian President Ivan Duque stated he wanted to lead a conservation pact with the other nations that share the Amazon rainforest with plans to present this to the UN General Assembly.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Attention to the wildfires increased in the week prior to the G7 summit discussions on August 24–26 in Biarritz, France, led by President Macron.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Macron stated his intent to open discussions related to the wildfires in the Brazilian part of the Amazon and Bolsonaro's response to them.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro expressed concern to United States president Donald Trump, that with Brazil not part of the G7, the country would be unrepresented in any such debate.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Trump offered to take the position of the Brazilian government to the meeting and said that the US government did not agree to discuss the issue without Brazil's presence.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Trump himself was absent from the environmental portion of the summit held on August 26, 2019, that discussed the fires and climate change, though members of his advisory team were in attendance.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] During the summit, Macron and Chilean president Sebastián Piñera negotiated with the other nations to authorize US$22 million in emergency funding to Amazonian countries to help fight the fires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Trump administration did not approve of the measure as the funding set certain requirements on its use.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] When the final negotiations were completed, Bolsonaro stated that he would refuse those funds for Brazil, claiming that Macron's interests were about protecting France's agricultural business in French Guiana from Brazil's competition.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro also criticised Macron by comparing the Amazon fires to the Notre-Dame de Paris fire earlier in 2019, suggesting Macron should take care of their internal fires before reaching out internationally.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The governors of the states of Brazil most affected by the fires pressured Bolsonaro to accept the aid given.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Bolsonaro later clarified that he would accept foreign aid for the fires, but only if Brazil has the authority to determine how it is used.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Brazil's Bolsonaro stated on August 28, 2019, that the countries sharing the Amazon rainforest, excluding Venezuela, will hold a summit in Colombia on September 6, 2019, to discuss the ongoing Amazon fire situation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Representatives from seven countries attended: Brazil, Colombia, Peru, Ecuador, Bolivia, Guyana and Suriname.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The countries signed a pact to coordinate monitoring of the Amazon forest and disaster response, and a better information network to coordinate their responses.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The pact will also seek cooperative efforts to reduce the need for illegal deforestation in their countries.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The media coverage had also broadly overshadowed the Amazon fires in Bolivia, Peru, and Paraguay by the fires and international impact of those in the BLA.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] The Amazon wildfires also occurred shortly after major wildfires reported in Greenland and Siberia after a globally hotter-than-average June and July, drawing away coverage of these natural disasters.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Some of these photographs shared on social media were from past fire events in the Amazon or from fires elsewhere.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Agence France-Presse and *El Comercio* published guides to help people "fact-check" on misleading photos.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] American actor Leonardo DiCaprio said his environmental organization Earth Alliance is donating $5 million to local groups and indigenous communities to help protect the Amazon.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] In a webcast on November 28, 2019, President Jair Bolsonaro said DiCaprio's donations encourage NGOs to set the fires in return for donations, a charge DiCaprio, Global Wildlife Conservation, and IUCN Species Survival Commission vehemently denied.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Instagram has been a platform for many celebrities who have spoken out about the wildfires such as Cara Delevingne, who posted a picture of the wildfires with the caption "#PrayForAmazonia".
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Other celebrities who made public contributions include actresses Vanessa Hudgens and Lana Condor, and Japanese musician Yoshiki.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] On August 26, 2019, Europe's richest man, Bernard Arnault, declared that his LVMH group will donate $11 million to aid in the fight against the Amazon rainforest wildfires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] American restaurateur Eddie Huang said he is going vegan as a result of the 2019 Amazon fires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] Khloé Kardashian urged her 98 million Instagram followers to adopt a plant-based diet for the same reason.
[src:amazon-rainforest/2019-amazon-rainforest-wildfires] 2021 single "Amazonia" by French metal band Gojira and its music video are a response the fires.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] The **41st parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 41 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] It crosses the Atlantic Ocean, the Indian Ocean, Australasia, the Pacific Ocean and South America.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] At this latitude the sun is visible for 15 hours, 8 minutes during the December solstice and 9 hours, 13 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] The **42nd parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 42 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] At this latitude the sun is visible for 15 hours, 15 minutes during the December solstice and 9 hours, 7 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] The alcohol brand 42 Below was named in part because the 42nd parallel South passes through New Zealand.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] The **43rd parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 43 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] On December solstice the sun is at 70.83 degrees in the sky and on June solstice it is at 23.17 degrees.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] At this latitude the sun is visible for 15 hours, 22 minutes during the Summer Solstice and 9 hours, 0 minutes during the Winter Solstice.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] The **44th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 44 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] At this latitude the sun is visible for 15 hours, 29 minutes during the December solstice and 8 hours, 53 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] The **45th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 45° south of the Earth's equator.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] It is the line that marks the theoretical halfway point between the equator and the South Pole.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] The true halfway point is 16.2 km (10.1 mi) south of this parallel because Earth is not a perfect sphere, but bulges at the equator and is flattened at the poles.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] Unlike its northern counterpart, almost all (97%) of it passes through open ocean.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] It crosses the South Atlantic Ocean, the Indian Ocean, Australasia (New Zealand and just south of Tasmania), the Southern Ocean, and Patagonia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] At this latitude, daytime lasts for 15 hours, 37 minutes during the December solstice and 8 hours, 46 minutes during the June solstice for the dates in 2024.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] This holds true regardless of longitude.
[src:amazon-rainforest/45th-parallel-south] The midday Sun stands 21.17° above the northern horizon at the June solstice, 68.83° at the December solstice, and exactly 45.0° at either equinox.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] A plant will abscise a part either to discard a member that is no longer necessary, such as a leaf during autumn, or a flower following fertilisation, or for the purposes of reproduction.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Most deciduous plants drop their leaves by abscission before winter, whereas evergreen plants continuously abscise their leaves.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Another form of abscission is fruit drop, when a plant abscises fruit while still immature in order to conserve resources needed to bring the remaining fruit to maturity.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] If a leaf is damaged, a plant may also abscise it to conserve water or photosynthetic efficiency, depending on the 'costs' to the plant as a whole.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] The abscission layer is a greenish-greyish color.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Abscission can also occur in premature leaves as a means of plant defense.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Premature leaf abscission has been shown to occur in response to infestation by gall aphids.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] By abscising leaves that have been made host to aphid galls, plants have been shown to massively diminish the pest population, as 98% of aphids in abscised galls died.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] The abscission is selective, and the chance of dropping leaves increases as the number of galls increases.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] A leaf with three or more galls was four times more likely to abscise than a leaf with one, and 20 times as likely to be dropped as a leaf without any galls.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Abscission occurs in a sequence of three steps: resorption, protective layer formation, and detachment.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] The latter two steps may occur in either order, depending on species.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Resorption involves degrading chlorophyll to extract the majority of its nutrients.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Nitrogen is found in chlorophyll and is often a limiting nutrient for plants, which need large quantities to form amino acids, nucleic acids, proteins, and certain plant hormones.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Once nitrogen and other nutrients have been extracted from chlorophyll, the nutrients will travel to other tissues of the plant.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Resorption is what causes leaves in the fall to change colors.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Carotenoids in the leaves are slower to degrade than chlorophyll, so autumn leaves appear yellow and orange.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Cells under the abscission zone divide and form a layer of cork cells.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Situated on both sides of the abscission zone are layers of parenchyma cells, which produce and inject suberin and lignin under the abscission zone into the new layer of cork cells.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Suberin and lignin create a durable and waterproof layer for the plant once the organ is detached.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] This step can occur in a variety of ways depending on the species but always occurs at the abscission zone.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Detachment can occur when layers of parenchyma cells secrete cell wall enzymes to self-digest the middle lamella, which holds the cell walls together at the abscission zone.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] This causes the cells of the abscission zone to break apart and the leaf or other plant part to fall off.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Another way detachment occurs is through imbibition of water.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] The plant cells at the abscission zone will take in a large amount of water, swell, and eventually burst, making the organ fall off.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Once detached, the protective layer of cork will be exposed.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] In deciduous trees, an abscission zone, also called a separation zone, is formed at the base of the petiole.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] It is composed of a top layer that has cells with weak walls, and a bottom layer that expands in the autumn, breaking the weak walls of the cells in the top layer.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] The reduction of chlorophyll production in leaves due to decreased sunlight in the autumn explains why some leaves turn yellow.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] However, the yellow color can attract aphids, so some trees turn the leaves red instead by injecting a bright pigment.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] The loss of chlorophyll may also contribute to the abscission process.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] A variety of reactive oxygen species (ROS) are generated by plants during times of stress (biotic and abiotic), including UV light, cool temperatures, excessive light, pathogens, parasites, and high salinity.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] The presence and continuous production of these ROS causes disruption in the homeostasis of the cellular components, leading to metabolic dysfunction and expression of cell wall-degrading enzymes (WDEs).
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] While researchers originally believed abscisic acid to be the hormone that stimulates abscission (for which the hormone was named), it was later proved that it does not play a primary role.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] In fact, auxin, a plant hormone, and ethylene have been implicated as prominent regulators of abscission signaling.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] The two compounds work in a synergistic fashion: As the auxin levels decrease, the flux of auxin to the abscission zone is reduced.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Exhaustion of auxin makes the abscission zone sensitive to ethylene.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] When the plant is then exposed to ethylene, gene expression of cell wall-degrading enzymes such as cellulase and polygalacturonase are activated.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] However, this is not to say that ethylene directly activates WDE gene expression, because the elements responsible for detecting ethylene have not been found in the gene's promoter region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/abscission] Dwindling auxin levels have also been implicated in autumn-leaf color change.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Intense extractive activity in the rubber industry, which reached its height in the early 20th century, attracted Brazilians from many regions to the state.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] From the mixture of sulista, southeastern Brazil, nordestino, and indigenous traditions arose a diverse cuisine.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Fluvial transport, concentrated on the Juruá and Moa rivers, in the western part of the state, and the Tarauacá and Envira rivers in the northwest, is the principal form of transportation, especially between November and June.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Heavy seasonal rains frequently make the BR-364 impassable in those months; it usually connects Rio Branco to Cruzeiro do Sul.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The name, which was given to the territory in 1904, and to the state in 1962, is derived from one of the local rivers, perhaps originates from the Tupi word *a'kir ü* "green river", or from the form *a'kir*, of the Tupi word *ker*, "to sleep, to rest".
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] It is believed more likely to be derived from *Aquiri*, a transliteration by European explorers of the term *Umákürü*, or *Uakiry*, from the Ipurinã dialect.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Another hypothesis is that Acquiri derives from *Yasi'ri*, or *Ysi'ri*, meaning "flowing or swift water".
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] According to one account, agriculturist João Gabriel de Carvalho Melo wrote during an 1878 trip on the Purús River to merchant Viscount of Santo Elias (from Pará), asking him for goods to be sent to the "mouth of the Aquiri River".
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] In Belém, the local merchant or his employees either misinterpreted Gabriel's handwriting, or he spelled the name wrong: the goods and invoice which Gabriel received were marked as having been sent to the Acre River.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Acre possesses some nicknames: the End of Brazil, The Rubber Tree State, the Latex State (from when it was a center of rubber production) and the Western End.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The native inhabitants of Acre are called *acr**i**ano**s***, in the singular *acr**i**an**o***.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Until the entry according to the Orthographic Agreement of 1990, the correct spelling was *acr**e**an**o*** in the singular and in the plural *acr**e**ano**s***.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] In 2009, with the new orthographic agreement, the change generated controversy between the Academy of Letters of Acre (Academia Acreana de Letras) and the Brazilian Academy of Letters (Academia Brasileira de Letras).
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The latter said that the change would mean the denial of the state's historical and cultural roots, by changing the last letter of the toponym from "E" to "I".
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The state of Acre occupies an area of 152,581 km2 (58,912 sq mi) (58,911 mi2) in the extreme west of Brazil.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] It is located at 70º west longitude and at 9º south latitude.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] In Brazil, the state is part of the North Region, forming borders with the states of Amazonas and Rondônia, and with two countries: Peru and Bolivia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Practically all of the terrain of the state of Acre is part of the low sandstone plateau, or terra firme, morphological unit which dominates most of the Brazilian Amazon.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] These terranes rise, in Acre, from the southeast to the northeast, with very tabular topography in general.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] In the extreme west is found the Serra da Contamana or Serra do Divisor, along the western border, with the highest altitudes in the state (609 m; 1,998 ft).
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The climate is hot and very humid, of the *Am* type in the Köppen climate classification system, and the monthly average temperatures vary between 24 and 27 °C (75 and 81 °F), being the lowest average of the North Region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The rainfall reaches an annual total of 2,100 mm (83 in), with a clear dry season in the months of June, July, and August.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The Amazon rainforest covers all of the state territory.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Very rich in rubber trees of the most valuable species (*Hevea brasiliensis*) and Brazil nut trees (*Bertholletia excelsa*), the forest guarantees that Acre is the greatest national producer of rubber and nuts.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Acre's principal rivers, mostly navigable during the wet season (the Juruá, Tarauacá, Envira, Purús, Iaco, and Acre), cross the state with almost parallel courses which converge only outside of its territory.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The largest recorded Black Caiman, measured at 7.7 meters (25 feet) and weighing 1,310 kg (2,890 lb), was shot in Acre in 1965.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The Amazon represents over half of the planet's remaining rainforests and comprises the largest and most species-rich tract of tropical rainforest in the world.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Wet tropical forests are the most species-rich biome, and tropical forests in the Americas are consistently more species-rich than the wet forests in Africa and Asia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] As the largest tract of tropical rainforest in the Americas, the Amazonian rainforests have unparalleled biodiversity.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] More than 1/3 of all species in the world live in the Amazon Rainforest.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The region of present-day Acre is thought to have been inhabited by Pre-Columbian civilizations since at least 2,100 years ago.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Evidence includes complex geoglyphs of this age found in the area.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The natives who crafted them are believed to have had a relatively advanced knowledge of this technology.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Since at least the early 15th century, the region has been inhabited by peoples who spoke Panoan languages; their territory was geographically close to that of the Inca.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] In the mid-18th century, the region was colonized by the Spanish and became part of the Viceroyalty of Peru.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Following the Peruvian and Bolivian wars of independence, which ended in 1826, the region and large portions around it became part of both Peru and Bolivia respectively, but independent of Spain and both states disputed the territory.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] It was a territory of the short-lived Peru–Bolivian Confederation (1836–1839), until the two countries separated and most of the region returned to Bolivian control.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The discovery of rubber tree groves in the region in the mid-19th century attracted numerous immigrants, especially from Brazil and Europe, seeking to build on the rubber boom.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Despite the increased numbers of Brazilians, the Treaty of Ayacucho (1867) determined that the region belonged to Bolivia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] By 1877, Acre's population was composed almost entirely of Brazilians coming from the Northeast.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] In 1899, Brazilian settlers in Acre declared an independent state known as the Republic of Acre.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Bolivia attempted to reassert control, but Brazilian resistance led to armed clashes, culminating in the Acre War.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] On 17 November 1903, the Treaty of Petrópolis was signed, transferring final possession of the region to Brazil.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Acre was incorporated as a Brazilian territory divided into three departments.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Brazil acquired the land for two million pounds sterling, with the territory taken from Mato Grosso under terms that also facilitated the construction of the Madeira-Mamoré railway.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Once the Acre War was over, Peru did not recognize the annexation of Acre until 1909, with the Velarde-Río Branco Treaty, where the borders between Peru and Brazil were defined.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] It was signed in Rio de Janeiro, on September 8, 1909, by the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Brazil, Baron of Rio Branco, and the plenipotentiary minister of Peru in Brazil, Hernán Velarde, by President Augusto B.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Leguía (first government) then ruled in Peru, and in Brazil by the president Nilo Pecanha, in order to solve the border problems between Peru and Brazil.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] On June 15, 1962, it was elevated to the category of state, and was the first to be governed by a woman, Iolanda Fleming, a teacher.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] During the early twentieth century, rubber seedlings were taken to Southeast Asia, where competitive plantations were established, reducing the importance of the Amazon in production.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] During the Second World War, Japanese forces took over the rubber tree groves of British Malaya.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Acre was called on to produce rubber for the Allied war effort.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The Rubber Soldiers, natives mostly of the Ceará plantation, increased production and provided critical supplies to the Allies.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Acre's decisive contribution to the Allied victory may have helped Brazil attract North American investment to form the National Steel Company (Companhia Siderúrgica Nacional) in the postwar era.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] This company aided in the industrialization of the Central-south, which did not yet possess basic heavy industries.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] On April 4, 2008, Acre won a judicial debate with the state of Amazonas in relation to the dispute surrounding the Cunha Gomes Line.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] It annexed part of the municipalities of Envira, Guajará, Boca do Acre, Pauini, Eirunepé and Ipixuna.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The territorial redefinition consolidated the incorporation of 1.2 million hectares of the Liberdade, Gregório, and Mogno forest complex to the territory of Acre, which corresponds to 11,583.87 km2 (4,472.56 sq mi).
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Since the 1970s, numerous geoglyphs, major geometric earthworks, have been discovered on deforested land in Acre, and dated to between 1–1250 AD.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] These are cited as evidence of complex Pre-Columbian societies.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The BBC's *Unnatural Histories* explored studies of this area, concluding that the Amazon rainforest, rather than being a pristine "wilderness", has been shaped by man for at least 11,000 years.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Traditional ancient practices included forest gardening.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Ondemar Dias is credited as the first to discover the geoglyphs in 1977.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Alceu Ranzi expanded their findings by flying over Acre.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] During the 17th century, Portuguese expeditions reached many of the far ends of present-day Brazil.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The expansion of the exploration to the west followed, and they reached lands under control by the Spanish colonies.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The two nations negotiated to establish their territories, under the Treaties of Madrid (1750) and San Ildefonso (1777).
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Both of the treaties were based on the explorations of Portuguese *bandeirante* Manoel Félix de Lima of the Guaporé and Madeira river basins.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The treaties established the riverbeds of the Mamoré and Guaporé to their maximum western limits on the left bank of the Javari as the border between the Spanish and Portuguese territories.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The Portuguese created the new royal captaincy of Mato Grosso (1751), stimulating settlement toward the frontier.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] New centers developed: Vila Bela (1752) on the banks of the Guaporé, Vila Maria (1778) on the Paraguay River, and Casalvasco (1783).
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Until the mid-19th century, there was little effort to settle the area systematically.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] At that time, the great virgin source of rubber attracted commercial interest, and development followed.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The empire was directed towards agricultural exports, based on coffee as the most important commodity.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The territories of the extreme west were unknown and usually overlooked.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] For example, although Cândido Mendes de Almeida's *Atlas of the Empire of Brazil* (1868), was considered a model of its time, geographers knew nothing of the Acre River and its principal tributaries, which did not appear at all in the atlas.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Some few armed bands of Brazilian explorers exploited the rural and unpopulated region, not knowing and little interested in whether they were "controlled" by Brazil, Peru, or Bolivia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] But the rubber boom of the mid-19th century, stimulated exploration by various expeditions to survey this resource and develop a plan for colonial settlement.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] For the most part, these expeditions took place on Bolivian land.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Exploitative activities, the industrial importance of the rubber reserves, and the penetration of Brazilian colonists in the region raised the attention of Bolivia, which solicited a better fixation of boundaries.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] After much failed negotiation, in 1867 the Treaty of Ayacucho was signed, which recognized the colonial *uti possidetis*, or use of that territory by Brazil.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] A border was established parallel to the confluence of the Beni and Mamoré rivers, running eastward to the headwaters of the Javari River, even though the source of this river was not yet known.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] As the price of rubber rose in the market, the demand for it grew.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Plantations multiplied in the valleys of the Acre, Purús and, farther west, the Tarauacá.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] In the year 1873–1874, in the drainage basin of the Purús, the population rose from around one thousand to four thousand inhabitants.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The Brazilian imperial government, already sensitive to the resulting offerings of rubber, considered the entire valley of the Purús to be Brazilian.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] In the second half of the 19th century, disturbances were registered in the demographic and geo-economic balance of the empire.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The coffee boom in the south attracted financial resources and workers, to detriment of the northeast.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The growing impoverishment of that region stimulated migratory waves to the states of Rio de Janeiro, Minas Gerais, and São Paulo.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The movement of population became particularly active during the prolonged drought of the northeastern interior, from 1877 to 1880.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Hundreds of Ceará indigenous people headed for the rubber plantations in search of work.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The Cearense migration reached the banks of the Juruá and accelerated the occupation of land which Bolivia would later reclaim.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The great fluvial rivers and their tributary systems were full of small ship fleets transporting colonists, goods, and supply material to the most isolated centers.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The governments of Amazonas and Pará quickly established *supply houses*, which financed various types of operations, guaranteed credit, and promoted the commercial incentive of the rubber tree groves.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The rubber race had the frantic urgency of gold rushes of the 18th century.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The situation drew the attention of the government to the economic use and development of an almost completely unknown area.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The activities of private businesses would enable the government to incorporate the new region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] In 1890, José Manuel Pando, a Bolivian official, alerted his government to the fact that more than three hundred rubber plantations had been developed in the Jura basin, and most were occupied by Brazilians on what was nominally Bolivian territory.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The Brazilian penetration had advanced west from the 64th meridian to beyond the 72nd, in an extension of one thousand kilometers, despite the borders having been established.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The Treaty of 1867 limited Brazil to land above the confluence of the Beni and Mamoré rivers.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] In 1895 a new commission to define the borders was created.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The Brazilian representative, Gregório Taumaturgo de Azevedo, resigned after verifying that the ratification of the Treaty of 1867 would harm the Brazilian rubber gatherers already settled in Bolivian territory.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] In 1899, the Bolivians established an administrative post in Puerto Alonso, exacting taxes and customs duties upon Brazilian activities.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The following year, Brazil accepted the sovereignty of Bolivia in the zone, when it officially recognized the old boundaries at the confluence of the Beni and Mamoré rivers.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Distant from the diplomatic process, the rubber workers judged their interests to have been cheated, and initiated insurrection movements.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Some of this was in response to brutal treatment and abuse by forces managed by the major rubber companies.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] In the same year that Bolivia established administration in Puerto Alonso (1899), two serious uprisings occurred.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] In April, a Cearense lawyer, José Carvalho, led an armed movement, which culminated in the expulsion of the Bolivian authorities.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Shortly thereafter, Bolivia began negotiations with an Anglo-American trust, the *Bolivian Syndicate*, in order to promote, with exceptional force (exacting of taxes, armed force), the political and economic incorporation of Acre into its territory.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The governor of Amazonas, Ramalho Júnior, informed of the agreement by a functionary of the Bolivian consulate in Belém, Luis Gálvez Rodríguez de Arias, sent military contingents forward to occupy Puerto Alonso.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Gálvez proclaimed the independence of Acre, in the form of a republic.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] He became its president with the acquiescence of the rubber gatherers.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Under protests from Bolivia, President Campos Sales abolished the ephemeral republic (March 1900).
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Bolivians, reinstated in the region, suffered in 1900 from the assault of the so-called Floriano Peixoto expedition, or "expedition of the poets".
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] It was made up of intellectual bohemians from Manaus.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Following brief fighting in the area surrounding Puerto Alonso, the expedition was completely scattered.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Ultimately, the Bolivian government signed a contract with the *Bolivian Syndicate* (July 1901).
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The Brazilian congress, shocked by the arbitrariness of the act, took measures, canceling commercial accords and navigation between the two countries, and suspending the right of travel to Bolivia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] At the same time, Brazilians organized a large armed assault on the disputed area.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The operations were led by a former student of the Military School of Rio Grande do Sul (Escola Militar do Rio Grande do Sul), José Plácido de Castro.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The rubber gatherers occupied the village of Xapuri in Alto Acre (August 1902), and took Bolivian officials into custody.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Finally, Plácido de Castro's forces besieged Puerto Alonso, proclaiming the Independent State of Acre, after the capitulation of Bolivian troops (February 1903).
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] José Plácido de Castro was proclaimed governor of the new Independent State of Acre, and he had to discuss the question of borders in the diplomatic sphere.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The Baron of Rio Branco, who had just assumed the role of Brazil's Minister of External Relations, immediately opened channels which were meant to have put an end to the question.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The simplest problem, with the *Bolivian Syndicate*, was resolved by Brazil paying one hundred and ten thousand pounds to renounce the contract (February 1903).
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Next, commercial relations were reestablished with Bolivia, while a part of the territory on the upper Purús and Juruá, militarily occupied in March 1903, was declared litigious.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Bolivia finally agreed to cede to Brazil an area of 142,800 km2 (55,100 sq mi), in exchange for two million pounds sterling, paid in two installments.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Brazil committed to the construction of a Madeira-Mamoré Railway, connecting Porto Velho to Guajará-Mirim, at the confluence of the Beni and Madeira rivers.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] These actions were ratified in the Treaty of Petrópolis (November 17, 1903), through which Brazil acquired the future territory, now state of Acre.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Peru had also claimed sovereignty over the entire territory of Acre and part of the state of Amazonas, based on historic colonial titles.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] After armed conflicts between Brazilians and Peruvians on the upper Purús and Juruá, a joint administration was established in those regions (1904).
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The studies to determine the borders proceeded until the end of 1909, when a treaty was signed that completed the political integration of Acre into Brazilian territory.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Exercising a prominent role in national exports until 1913, when rubber was introduced to European and North American markets, Acre enjoyed a period of great prosperity.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] At the start of the 20th century, in a period of less than ten years, it grew to have more than 50,000 inhabitants.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] From 1946 on, the federal government undertook actions to revive the economy of the Amazon Basin, and to include it in regional development projects.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The departmental administration was exercised until 1921 by mayors appointed by the President of Brazil.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] At that time the arrangements were altered, passing the administration to a governor.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The second Constitution of Brazil (1934) conceded to Acre the right to elect representatives to the National Congress of Brazil.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] During the Estado Novo (New State) political ideas involving the valorization of the interior took hold, with the intention of promoting the articulation of more isolated areas.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Thereafter, the vote of 1946 commended the channeling of budgetary resources from the Union to the Amazon, determining that the Territory of Acre would be elevated to the condition of state as soon as its revenue reached the equivalent of the lowest state tax exaction.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] In the 1960s, the second cycle of efforts to accelerate the progress of the Amazon area was begun with the Superintendency of the Development of the Amazon (Superintendência do Desenvolvimento da Amazônia or SUDAM, 1966).
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Planning politics developed, therefore, destined to correct the demographic, economic, and political distortions of national integration.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] According to the IBGE of 2022, there were 830,018 people residing in the state. making Acre the third least populated state.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The population density was 4.5 inh./km2.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] As of 2022, Acre is one of two states in Brazil where Protestants outnumber Catholics.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Portuguese is the official national language, and thus the primary language taught in schools.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] English and Spanish are also part of the official high school curriculum.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The service sector is the largest component of GDP at 66%, followed by the industrial sector at 28.1%.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Agriculture represents 5.9%, of GDP (2004).
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Acre exports: wood 85.6%, poultry (chicken and wild turkey) 4.7%, wood products 1.7% (2002).
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Share of the Brazilian economy: 0.2% (2005).
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Rio Branco International Airport is located in a rural zone of the municipality of Rio Branco, in the state of Acre.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] It was opened on November 2, 1999, with a unique characteristic: it moved 22 kilometers away from the previous airport site.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Rio Branco Airport serves domestic and international flights (by scheduled carriers and air taxi firms) along with general and military aviation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The terminal can receive 270 thousand passengers a year and serves an average of 14 daily operations.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Cruzeiro do Sul International Airport is located 18 kilometers away from the city center, which helps access to the Alto Juruá region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] It was opened on October 28, 1970, and absorbed by Infraero on March 31, 1980.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The airport infrastructure was built in 1976 by the municipal government.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] In 1994, the runway was completely renovated.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] There are domestic airports at Tarauacá, Sena Madureira and Brasiléia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Rio Branco provides visitors and residents with various sport activities.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The Arena da Floresta stadium in Rio Branco was one of the 18 candidates to host games in the 2014 FIFA World Cup, which was held in Brazil, but did not make it to the final 12 chosen.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Despite being the only state that fought to be Brazilian (Acre War), Acre's culture is similar to that of other Northern Brazilian states, however, there is a high consumption of Northeastern Brazilian culture.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The ritual implies in drinking a tea, including children and the elderly.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The members wear uniforms and sing the hymnal.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The best-known dish consumed by Acreans is called Baixaria.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The typical food uses duck, tucupi, cassava flour and pirarucu fish, in addition to the huge variety of Amazonian fruits inherited from the Indigenous peoples.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] Some singers, activists and artists from Acre: João Donato, Sansão Campos Pereira, Chico Mendes, Sergio Souto and Tião Natureza.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] It is a variation of the flags used by the secessionist state of Acre, with the yellow and green parts exchanged and mirrored.
[src:amazon-rainforest/acre-state] The yellow color symbolizes peace, green hope, and the star symbolizes the light which guided those who worked to make Acre a state of Brazil.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] An **aerosol** is a suspension of fine solid particles or liquid droplets in air or another gas.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Aerosols can be generated from natural or human causes.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The scientific term *aerosol* refers to the mixture of particulates in gas, and not to the particulate matter alone.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The liquid or solid particles in an aerosol have diameters typically less than 1 μm.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Larger particles with a significant settling speed make the mixture a suspension, although the distinction is not clear.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Examples of natural aerosols are fog, mist, and dust from geological or biological sources.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Certain infections spread by means of small droplets in the breath, sometimes called bioaerosols.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Several types of atmospheric aerosol have a significant effect on Earth's climate: volcanic, desert dust, sea-salt, originating from biogenic sources and human-made.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Volcanic aerosol forms in the stratosphere after an eruption as droplets of sulfuric acid that can prevail for up to two years, and reflect sunlight, lowering temperature.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Desert dust, mineral particles blown to high altitudes, absorb heat and may be responsible for inhibiting storm cloud formation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] In everyday language, *aerosol* often refers to a dispensing system that delivers a consumer product from a spray can.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Other examples of human caused aerosols include perfume from atomizers, medical treatments for respiratory illnesses, dust from material or industrial sources, smoke, irrigation mist, sprayed pesticides, particulate air pollutants, and mist from the discharge at hydroelectric dams.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Human-made sulfate aerosols, primarily from burning oil and coal, affect the behavior of clouds.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] When aerosols absorb pollutants, it facilitates the deposition of pollutants to the surface of the earth as well as to bodies of water.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] This has the potential to be damaging to both the environment and human health.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Ship tracks are clouds that form around the exhaust released by ships into the still ocean air.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Water molecules collect around the tiny particles (aerosols) from exhaust to form a cloud seed.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] More and more water accumulates on the seed until a visible cloud is formed.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] In the case of ship tracks, the cloud seeds are stretched over a long narrow path where the wind has blown the ship's exhaust, so the resulting clouds resemble long strings over the ocean.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The warming caused by human-produced greenhouse gases has been somewhat offset by the cooling effect of human-produced aerosols.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] In 2020, regulations on fuel significantly cut sulfur dioxide emissions from international shipping by approximately 80%, leading to an unexpected global geoengineering termination shock.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Aerosol is defined as a suspension system of solid or liquid particles in a gas.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] An aerosol includes both the particles and the suspending gas, which is usually air.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Meteorologists and climatologists often refer to them as particle matter, while the classification in sizes ranges like PM2.5 or PM10, is useful in the field of atmospheric pollution as these size range play a role in ascertain the harmful effects in human health.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Donnan presumably first used the term *aerosol* during World War I to describe an aero-solution, clouds of microscopic particles in air.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] This term developed analogously to the term hydrosol, a colloid system with water as the dispersed medium.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] *Primary aerosols* contain particles introduced directly into the gas; *secondary aerosols* form through gas-to-particle conversion.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Key aerosol groups include sulfates, organic carbon, black carbon, nitrates, mineral dust, and sea salt, they usually clump together to form a complex mixture.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Various types of aerosol, classified according to physical form and how they were generated, include dust, fume, mist, smoke and fog.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] There are several measures of aerosol concentration.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Environmental science and environmental health often use the *mass concentration* (*M*), defined as the mass of particulate matter per unit volume, in units such as μg/m3.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Also commonly used is the *number concentration* (*N*), the number of particles per unit volume, in units such as number per m3 or number per cm3.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Particle size has a major influence on particle properties, and the aerosol particle radius or diameter (*dp*) is a key property used to characterise aerosols.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] A *monodisperse* aerosol, producible in the laboratory, contains particles of uniform size.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Most aerosols, however, as *polydisperse* colloidal systems, exhibit a range of particle sizes.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Liquid droplets are almost always nearly spherical, but scientists use an *equivalent diameter* to characterize the properties of various shapes of solid particles, some very irregular.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The equivalent diameter is the diameter of a spherical particle with the same value of some physical property as the irregular particle.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The *equivalent volume diameter* (*de*) is defined as the diameter of a sphere of the same volume as that of the irregular particle.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Also commonly used is the aerodynamic diameter, *da*.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Several types of atmospheric aerosol have a significant effect on Earth's climate: volcanic, desert dust, sea-salt, that originating from biogenic sources and human-made.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Although all hydrometeors, solid and liquid, can be described as aerosols, a distinction is commonly made between such dispersions (i.e. clouds and precipitation) containing relatively large water drops or ice crystals, and aerosol particles.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The presence of aerosols in the Earth's atmosphere can influence its climate, as well as human health.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Volcanic eruptions release large amounts of sulphuric acid, hydrogen sulfide and hydrochloric acid into the atmosphere.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] These gases represent aerosols and eventually return to earth as acid rain, having a number of adverse effects on the environment and human life.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Aerosols interact with the Earth's energy budget in two ways, directly and indirectly.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Aerosol particles with an effective diameter smaller than 10 μm can enter the bronchi, while the ones with an effective diameter smaller than 2.5 μm can enter as far as the gas exchange region in the lungs, which can be hazardous to human health.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] For a monodisperse aerosol, a single number—the particle diameter—suffices to describe the size of the particles.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] However, more complicated particle-size distributions describe the sizes of the particles in a polydisperse aerosol.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] This distribution defines the relative amounts of particles, sorted according to size.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] One approach to defining the particle size distribution uses a list of the sizes of every particle in a sample.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] However, this approach proves tedious to ascertain in aerosols with millions of particles and awkward to use.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Another approach splits the size range into intervals and finds the number (or proportion) of particles in each interval.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The particle size distribution can be approximated.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The normal distribution usually does not suitably describe particle size distributions in aerosols because of the skewness associated with a long tail of larger particles.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Also for a quantity that varies over a large range, as many aerosol sizes do, the width of the distribution implies negative particles sizes, which is not physically realistic.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] However, the normal distribution can be suitable for some aerosols, such as test aerosols, certain pollen grains and spores.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The log-normal distribution has no negative values, can cover a wide range of values, and fits many observed size distributions reasonably well.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] For low values of the Reynolds number (<1), true for most aerosol motion, Stokes' law describes the force of resistance on a solid spherical particle in a fluid.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] However, Stokes' law is only valid when the velocity of the gas at the surface of the particle is zero.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] For small particles (< 1 μm) that characterize aerosols, however, this assumption fails.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] To account for this failure, one can introduce the Cunningham correction factor, always greater than 1.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] This allows us to calculate the terminal velocity of a particle undergoing gravitational settling in still air.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] is the terminal settling velocity of the particle.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The terminal velocity can also be derived for other kinds of forces.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] If Stokes' law holds, then the resistance to motion is directly proportional to speed.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] To account for the effect of the shape of non-spherical particles, a correction factor known as the *dynamic shape factor* is applied to Stokes' law.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The aerodynamic diameter of an irregular particle is defined as the diameter of the spherical particle with a density of 1000 kg/m3 and the same settling velocity as the irregular particle.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] One can apply the aerodynamic diameter to particulate pollutants or to inhaled drugs to predict where in the respiratory tract such particles deposit.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Pharmaceutical companies typically use aerodynamic diameter, not geometric diameter, to characterize particles in inhalable drugs.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The previous discussion focused on single aerosol particles.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] In contrast, *aerosol dynamics* explains the evolution of complete aerosol populations.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The concentrations of particles will change over time as a result of many processes.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] External processes that move particles outside a volume of gas under study include diffusion, gravitational settling, and electric charges and other external forces that cause particle migration.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] A second set of processes internal to a given volume of gas include particle formation (nucleation), evaporation, chemical reaction, and coagulation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] A differential equation called the *Aerosol General Dynamic Equation* (GDE) characterizes the evolution of the number density of particles in an aerosol due to these processes.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] As particles and droplets in an aerosol collide with one another, they may undergo coalescence or aggregation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] This process leads to a change in the aerosol particle-size distribution, with the mode increasing in diameter as total number of particles decreases.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] On occasion, particles may shatter apart into numerous smaller particles; however, this process usually occurs primarily in particles too large for consideration as aerosols.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] where $\lambda$ is the mean free path of the suspending gas and d is the diameter of the particle.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] For particles in the *free molecular regime*, *Kn* >> 1; particles small compared to the mean free path of the suspending gas.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] In this regime, particles interact with the suspending gas through a series of "ballistic" collisions with gas molecules.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] As such, they behave similarly to gas molecules, tending to follow streamlines and diffusing rapidly through Brownian motion.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] where *a* is the particle radius, *P*∞ and *PA* are the pressures far from the droplet and at the surface of the droplet respectively, *kb* is the Boltzmann constant, *T* is the temperature, *CA* is mean thermal velocity and *α* is mass accommodation coefficient.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The derivation of this equation assumes constant pressure and constant diffusion coefficient.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Particles are in the *continuum regime* when Kn << 1.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] In this regime, the particles are big compared to the mean free path of the suspending gas, meaning that the suspending gas acts as a continuous fluid flowing round the particle.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The *transition regime* contains all the particles in between the free molecular and continuum regimes or *Kn* ≈ 1.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The forces experienced by a particle are a complex combination of interactions with individual gas molecules and macroscopic interactions.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] where *I*cont is the mass flux in the continuum regime.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] This formula is called the Fuchs-Sutugin interpolation formula.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] These equations do not take into account the heat release effect.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Aerosol partitioning theory governs condensation on and evaporation from an aerosol surface, respectively.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Condensation of mass causes the mode of the particle-size distributions of the aerosol to increase; conversely, evaporation causes the mode to decrease.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Nucleation is the process of forming aerosol mass from the condensation of a gaseous precursor, specifically a vapor.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Net condensation of the vapor requires supersaturation, a partial pressure greater than its vapor pressure.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Chemical reactions may increase the partial pressure of a gas or lower its vapor pressure.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The addition of additional vapor to the system may lower the equilibrium vapor pressure according to Raoult's law.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] There are two types of nucleation processes.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Gases preferentially condense onto surfaces of pre-existing aerosol particles, known as **heterogeneous nucleation**.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] This process causes the diameter at the mode of particle-size distribution to increase with constant number concentration.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] With sufficiently high supersaturation and no suitable surfaces, particles may condense in the absence of a pre-existing surface, known as **homogeneous nucleation**.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] This results in the addition of very small, rapidly growing particles to the particle-size distribution.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Water coats particles in aerosols, making them *activated*, usually in the context of forming a cloud droplet (such as natural cloud seeding by aerosols from trees in a forest).
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Following the Kelvin equation (based on the curvature of liquid droplets), smaller particles need a higher ambient relative humidity to maintain equilibrium than larger particles do.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] where $p_{s}$ is the saturation vapor pressure above a particle at equilibrium (around a curved liquid droplet), *p*0 is the saturation vapor pressure (flat surface of the same liquid) and *S* is the saturation ratio.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] where *rp* droplet radius, *σ* surface tension of droplet, *ρ* density of liquid, *M* molar mass, *T* temperature, and *R* molar gas constant.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Aerosols can either be measured in-situ or with remote sensing techniques either ground-based on airborne-based.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Particles can deposit in the nose, mouth, pharynx and larynx (the head airways region), deeper within the respiratory tract (from the trachea to the terminal bronchioles), or in the alveolar region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The location of deposition of aerosol particles within the respiratory system strongly determines the health effects of exposure to such aerosols.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] This phenomenon led people to invent aerosol samplers that select a subset of the aerosol particles that reach certain parts of the respiratory system.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Examples of these subsets of the particle-size distribution of an aerosol, important in occupational health, include the inhalable, thoracic, and respirable fractions.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The fraction that can enter each part of the respiratory system depends on the deposition of particles in the upper parts of the airway.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The inhalable fraction of particles, defined as the proportion of particles originally in the air that can enter the nose or mouth, depends on external wind speed and direction and on the particle-size distribution by aerodynamic diameter.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The thoracic fraction is the proportion of the particles in ambient aerosol that can reach the thorax or chest region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The respirable fraction is the proportion of particles in the air that can reach the alveolar region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] To measure the respirable fraction of particles in air, a pre-collector is used with a sampling filter.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The pre-collector excludes particles as the airways remove particles from inhaled air.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The sampling filter collects the particles for measurement.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] It is common to use cyclonic separation for the pre-collector, but other techniques include impactors, horizontal elutriators, and large pore membrane filters.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] Two alternative size-selective criteria, often used in atmospheric monitoring, are PM10 and PM2.5.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] PM10 is defined by ISO as *particles which pass through a size-selective inlet with a 50% efficiency cut-off at 10 μm aerodynamic diameter* and PM2.5 as *particles which pass through a size-selective inlet with a 50% efficiency cut-off at 2.5 μm aerodynamic diameter*.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] PM10 corresponds to the "thoracic convention" as defined in ISO 7708:1995, Clause 6; PM2.5 corresponds to the "high-risk respirable convention" as defined in ISO 7708:1995, 7.1.
[src:amazon-rainforest/aerosol] The United States Environmental Protection Agency replaced the older standards for particulate matter based on Total Suspended Particulate with another standard based on PM10 in 1987 and then introduced standards for PM2.5 (also known as fine particulate matter) in 1997.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Africa straddles the equator and the prime meridian.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The continent is surrounded by the Mediterranean Sea to the north, the Arabian plate and the Gulf of Aqaba to the northeast, the Indian Ocean to the southeast and the Atlantic Ocean to the west.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] France, Italy, Portugal, Spain, and Yemen have parts of their territories located on African geographical soil, mostly in the form of islands.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The continent includes Madagascar and various archipelagos.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] It contains 54 fully recognised sovereign states, eight cities and islands that are part of non-African states, and two *de facto* independent states with limited or no recognition.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] This count does not include Malta and Sicily, which are geologically part of the African continent.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Algeria is Africa's largest country by area, and Nigeria is its largest by population.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] African nations cooperate through the establishment of the African Union, which is headquartered in Addis Ababa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Africa is highly biodiverse; it is the continent with the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] However, Africa is also heavily affected by a wide range of environmental issues, including desertification, deforestation, water scarcity, and pollution.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] These entrenched environmental concerns are expected to worsen as climate change impacts Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The UN Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change has identified Africa as the continent most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The history of Africa is long, complex, and varied, and has often been under-appreciated by the global historical community.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In African societies the oral word is revered, and they have generally recorded their history via oral tradition, which has led anthropologists to term them "oral civilisations", contrasted with "literate civilisations" which pride the written word.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] African culture is rich and diverse both within and between the continent's regions, encompassing art, cuisine, music and dance, religion, and dress.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Africa, particularly Eastern Africa, is widely accepted to be the place of origin of humans and the Hominidae clade, also known as the great apes.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The earliest hominids and their ancestors have been dated to around 7 million years ago, and *Homo sapiens* (modern human) are believed to have originated in Africa 350,000 to 260,000 years ago.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Throughout history the continent saw the rise and fall of many kingdoms and empires, such as Ancient Egypt, Makuria, the Fatimids, Mali, the Asante, Kongo, the Luba, Bunyoro, Great Zimbabwe, Imerina, and the Zulu.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Despite the predominance of states, many societies were heterarchical and stateless.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Slave trades created various diasporas, especially in the Americas.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] From the late-19th century to early 20th century, driven by the Second Industrial Revolution, most of Africa was rapidly conquered and colonised by European nations, save for Ethiopia and Liberia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] European rule had significant impacts on Africa's societies, and colonies were maintained for the purpose of economic exploitation and extraction of natural resources.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Most present states emerged from a process of decolonisation following World War II, and established the Organisation of African Unity in 1963, the predecessor to the African Union.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The nascent countries decided to keep their colonial borders, with traditional power structures used in governance to varying degrees.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Under Roman rule, Carthage became the capital of the province then named *Africa Proconsularis*, following the Roman victory over the Carthaginians in the Third Punic War in 146 BC, which also included the coastal part of modern Libya.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The Latin suffix *-ica* can sometimes be used to denote a land (e.g., in *Celtica* from *Celtae*, as used by Julius Caesar).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The later Muslim region of Ifriqiya, following its conquest of the Byzantine (Eastern Roman) Empire's *Exarchatus Africae*, also preserved a form of the name.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] According to the Romans, Africa lies to the west of Egypt, while "Asia" was used to refer to Anatolia and lands to the east.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] A definite line was drawn between the two continents by the geographer Ptolemy (85–165 CE), indicating Alexandria along the Prime Meridian and making the isthmus of Suez and the Red Sea the boundary between Asia and Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] As Europeans came to understand the real extent of the continent, the idea of "Africa" expanded with their knowledge.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In accordance with African cosmology, African historical consciousness viewed historical change and continuity, order and purpose within the framework of man and his environment, the gods, and his ancestors, and he believed himself part of a holistic spiritual entity.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In African societies, the historical process is largely a communal one, with eyewitness accounts, hearsay, reminiscences, and occasionally visions, dreams, and hallucinations crafted into narrative oral traditions which are performed and transmitted through generations.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In oral traditions time is sometimes mythical and social, and ancestors were considered historical actors.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Mind and memory shapes traditions, as events are condensed over time and crystallise into clichés.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Oral tradition can be exoteric or esoteric.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] It speaks to people according to their understanding, unveiling itself in accordance with their aptitudes.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Africa is considered by most paleoanthropologists to be the oldest inhabited territory on Earth, with the Human species originating from the continent.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] During the mid-20th century, anthropologists discovered many fossils and evidence of human occupation perhaps as early as seven million years ago ("Before Present"; BP).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Fossil remains of several species of early apelike humans thought to have evolved into modern humans, such as *Australopithecus afarensis* radiometrically dated to approximately 3.9–3.0 million years BP, *Paranthropus boisei* (c.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] 2.3–1.4 million years BP) and *Homo ergaster* (c.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] 1.9 million–600,000 years BP) have been discovered.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] After the evolution of *Homo sapiens* approximately 350,000 to 260,000 years BP in Africa, the continent was mainly populated by groups of hunter-gatherers.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] These first modern humans left Africa and populated the rest of the globe during the Out of Africa II migration dated to approximately 50,000 years BP, exiting the continent either across Bab-el-Mandeb over the Red Sea, the Strait of Gibraltar in Morocco, or the Isthmus of Suez in Egypt.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Other migrations of modern humans within the African continent have been dated to that time, with evidence of early human settlement found in Southern Africa, Southeast Africa, North Africa, and the Sahara.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] However, the warming and drying climate meant that by 5,000 BC, the Sahara region was becoming increasingly dry and hostile.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Around 3500 BC, due to a tilt in the Earth's orbit, the Sahara experienced a period of rapid desertification.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The domestication of cattle in Africa preceded agriculture and seems to have existed alongside hunter-gatherer cultures.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] It is speculated that by 6,000 BC, cattle were domesticated in North Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In West Africa, a wet phase ushered in an expanding rainforest and wooded savanna from Senegal to Cameroon.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Between 9,000 and 5,000 BC, Niger–Congo speakers domesticated the oil palm and raffia palm.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Black-eyed peas and voandzeia (African groundnuts), were domesticated, followed by okra and kola nuts.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Since most of the plants grew in the forest, the Niger–Congo speakers invented polished stone axes for clearing forest.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Pygmies are thought to have inhabited Central Africa for many millennia, splitting into eastern and western groups around 5,000 BP.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Over 150,000 BP, there was an early dispersal of anatomically modern humans to Southern Africa, equated with the modern-day Khoisan who have preserved their traditional hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] From 3500 BC, nomes (ruled by nomarchs) coalesced to form the kingdoms of Lower Egypt and Upper Egypt in northeast Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Around 3100 BC Upper Egypt conquered Lower Egypt to unify Egypt under the 1st dynasty, with the process of consolidation and assimilation completed by the time of the 3rd dynasty who formed the Old Kingdom of Egypt in 2686 BC.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The Kingdom of Kerma emerged around this time to become the dominant force in Nubia, controlling territory as large as Egypt between the 1st and 4th cataracts of the Nile.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The height of the Old Kingdom saw the construction of many great pyramids, though under the 6th dynasty power gradually decentralised to the nomarchs, culminating in the disintegration of the kingdom, exacerbated by drought and famine.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Around 2055 BC, the 11th dynasty, based in Thebes, conquered the others to form the Middle Kingdom of Egypt, and the 12th dynasty expanded into Lower Nubia at the expense of Kerma.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Around 1700 BC, the Middle Kingdom fractured in two, and the Hyksos (a militaristic people from Palestine) invaded and conquered Lower Egypt, while Kerma coordinated invasions deep into Egypt to reach its greatest extent.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In 1550 BC, the 18th dynasty expelled the Hyksos, and established the New Kingdom of Egypt.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The New Kingdom conquered the Levant from the Canaanites, Mittani, Amorites, and Hittites, and extinguished Kerma, incorporating Nubia into the empire, and sending the Egyptian empire into its golden age.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Internal struggles, drought, famine, and invasions by a confederation of seafaring peoples contributed to the New Kingdom's collapse in 1069 BC.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The New Kingdom's collapse liberated the Kingdom of Kush in Nubia, which manoeuvred into power in Upper Egypt and conquered Lower Egypt in 754 BC to form the Kushite Empire.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The Kushites ruled for a century and oversaw a revival in pyramid building, until they were driven out of Egypt by the Assyrians in 663 BC in reprisal for their expansion towards the Assyrian Empire.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The Assyrians installed a puppet dynasty that later gained independence and once more unified Egypt, until it was conquered by the Achaemenid Empire in 525 BC.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Egypt briefly regained independence from the Achaemenids under the 28th dynasty from 404 to 343 BC.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The conquest of Achaemenid Egypt by Alexander the Great in 332 BC marked the beginning of Hellenistic rule and the installation of the Macedonian Ptolemaic dynasty in Egypt.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The Ptolemaics lost their holdings outside of Africa to the Seleucids in the Syrian Wars, expanded into Cyrenaica, and briefly occupied part of Kush in the 3rd century BC.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the 1st century BC, Ptolemaic Egypt became entangled in a Roman civil war, leading to its conquest by the Romans in 30 BC.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Kush persisted as a major regional power until, having been weakened from internal rebellion amid worsening climatic conditions, invasions by Aksum and the Noba caused their disintegration into Makuria, Alodia, and Nobatia around the 5th century AD.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, there was the Land of Punt, a kingdom on the Red Sea which was a close trading partner of Ancient Egypt in the 3rd and 2nd millennia BC.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Rodolfo Fattovich equated it to the Gash Group in the Sudanese-Eritrean lowlands, and some scholars have hypothesised modern-day Somalia, while Kenneth Kitchen and Felix Chami locate it on Zanzibar Island.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the Eritrean-Ethiopian Highlands, the kingdom of dʿmt rose c.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] 980 BC as the region was incorporated into global trading networks, and it exhibited Sabaean influences which most scholars attribute to a small migration of Sabaeans and their assimilation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Several scholars consider there to have been other contemporaneous states, and dʿmt's collapse in the mid-1st century BC saw the region inhabited by small polities.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Modern-day Somalia was inhabited by nomadic pastoralists, and along the Horn's coast there were many ancient Somali city-states that thrived off of the wider Red Sea trade, and enjoyed a lucrative monopoly on cinnamon from Ancient India due to their freedom from Roman interference.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the 1st century AD, the Kingdom of Aksum rose from a city-state to rule much of the northern Ethiopian-Eritrean Highlands and the Red Sea port of Adulis.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Aksum was described as one of the four great powers by Persian prophet Mani in the 3rd century.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Aksum's king converted from traditional religion to Christianity in the 4th century, gradually followed by the population.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the 6th century, Aksum conquered South Arabia, though struggled to maintain control over it, and began to gradually lose its dominance over Red Sea trade to Persians and Arabs.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Northwest Africa (the Maghreb) was inhabited by Berber semi-nomadic pastoralists.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the 1st millennium BC, Phoenician migration and settlement came in search for precious metals in the Gulf of Tunis.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] This grew into Ancient Carthage after gaining independence from Phoenicia in the 6th century BC, and they built an extensive trading empire with a strict mercantile network.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Carthage's collapse and conquest by Rome in the Punic Wars (3rd and 2nd centuries BC) saw Numidia and Mauretania become major powers in the Maghreb.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 2nd century BC Mauretania fought alongside Numidia's Jugurtha against the Romans in the Jugurthine War after he had usurped the Numidian throne from a Roman ally.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Together they inflicted heavy casualties, with the war only ending inconclusively when Mauretania's Bocchus I sold out Jugurtha to the Romans.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, both came under direct Roman rule.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] While traditional religion predominated among Berbers, some people converted to Christianity.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the 5th century AD the Vandals conquered Roman Africa before the fall of Rome, though the province was reconquered by the Byzantines a century later.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Large swathes of indigenous peoples regained self-governance in Masuna and its numerous successor polities in the Maghreb, including the kingdoms of Ouarsenis, Aurès, and Altava.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the western Sahel the rise of settled communities occurred largely as a result of the domestication of millet and of sorghum, and cattle pastoralism began c.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Extensive east-west belts of deserts, grasslands, and forests from north to south were crucial for the moulding of their respective societies and meant that symbiotic trade relations developed in response to the differing environments.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Beginning around 4000 BC, the Tichitt culture in modern-day Mauritania and Mali is the oldest known complexly organised society in West Africa, while others included the Kintampo culture in modern-day Ghana, the Nok culture in modern-day Nigeria, and the Daima culture around Lake Chad.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 3rd century AD, a wet period in the Sahel created areas for human habitation and exploitation that had not been habitable for the best part of a millennium.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The Ghana Empire (also called *Wagadu*) rose out of the Tichitt culture, growing wealthy following the introduction of the camel to the western Sahel, which revolutionised the trans-Saharan trade that linked their capital and Aoudaghost with Tahert and Sijilmasa in North Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Soninke tradition holds that the final founding of Wagadu occurred after Dinga did a deal with Bida, a serpent deity who was guarding a well, to sacrifice one maiden a year in exchange for assurance regarding plenty of rainfall and gold supply.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Based on large tumuli scattered across West Africa dating to this period, several scholars have speculated that there were further simultaneous and preceding states relative to Wagadu.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the Grasslands of northwestern Cameroon, Bantu-speaking agriculturalists started to gradually migrate south sometime between 5000 BC and 3000 BC.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Despite intensive research, the cause of the migrations, and that of the directions taken, is still unclear, however there is consensus that there were multiple dispersal events.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Around 1500 BC, Bantu speakers reached central Cameroon.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The 'Western Stream' likely followed the coast and the major rivers of the Congo system southwards to reach the southern fringe of the Congolian Rainforest around 500 BC (some may have used the sea to circumvent the rainforest).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Their arrival coincided with the spread of iron metallurgy through Central Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Meanwhile, the 'Eastern Stream' travelled either the northern fringe of the rainforest or the Ubangi River eastwards, and reached just west of Lake Victoria around 500 BC.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] While there, Bantu speakers adopted iron metallurgy from Cushitic speakers already present, and coexisted with them.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Dispersal from the Great Lakes region occurred in two more streams.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] One went west to meet the Western Stream in the DR Congo and Angola, while the other went south and spread across Eastern and Southern Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, Bantu speakers reached central modern-day Tanzania and near Dar es Salaam, before rapidly moving southwards along the coast to reach modern-day Kwazulu Natal in South Africa around the 3rd century AD.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Throughout this, Bantu speakers displaced, replaced, or intermarried with and absorbed hunter-gatherer and agricultural groups.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the 7th and 8th centuries, as part of the Arab conquests which sought to spread Islamic rule, the Rashidun and Umayyad caliphates conquered North Africa at the expense of the Byzantine Empire and Berber leaders such as Kusaila and Kahina.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Large numbers of Berber and Coptic people willingly converted to Islam, and followers of Abrahamic religions ('People of the Book') were protected, though followers of Berber traditional religion were violently oppressed.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the 8th century the Berber Revolt rocked the Caliphate and Berber dynasties took control over the Maghreb, while the Tulunids briefly controlled Egypt.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the 10th century, the Fatimids rose to power in modern-day Tunisia, established a rival caliphate, and conquered Egypt, before expanding into the Middle East.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the 11th century the Almoravids conquered the Maghreb and intervened in the Christian reconquest of Iberia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Saladin, a Fatimid vizier, usurped power in the 12th century and established the Ayyubid dynasty which restored Egyptian prestige, while the Almohad revolution deposed the Almoravids to the east.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] After Christian gains in Iberia in the 13th century, the Almohads disintegrated into the Marinids, Zayyanids, and Hafsids in modern-day Morocco, Algeria, and Tunisia respectively.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the face of Mongol expansion, Mamluk generals seized power in Egypt and expanded into the Middle East.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the early-16th century, the Ottoman Empire rapidly conquered North Africa (save for Morocco, now under Saadi rule) to counter Spanish expansionism.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the following centuries, over a million Europeans are estimated to have been captured and enslaved by Barbary corsairs.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The Ottoman regencies became more independent during the 18th century.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the central Sahel around Lake Chad, the Kanem–Bornu Empire ruled from the 6th century, and projected power over the Hausa Kingdoms.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] To the east during 7th century, Makuria conquered Nobatia to become the dominant power in the region and resisted Muslim expansion.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] They later entered a severe decline following civil war and Arab migrations to the Sudan and had disintegrated by the 15th century, giving rise to the Funj Sultanate.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The Tunjur empire's collapse in the central Sudan saw the rise of the Bagirmi, Wadai, and Darfur sultanates, which frequently raided the populations to their south for slaves.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, Aksum lost control of the Red Sea, and its isolation from Christendom caused Ethiopian society to introspect and take inspiration from the Old Testament.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Islamised Beja invaded the Ethiopian Highlands, forcing Aksum to migrate south, where, according to tradition, Aksum's expansion was met by a Jewish or traditionalist queen who destroyed the state c.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] During the 13th century, hegemony in the Horn was contested by the Christian Zagwe, the Muslims of Shewa, and the traditionalist Damot; the Solomonic dynasty overthrew the Zagwe to found the Ethiopian Empire, while Shewa was replaced by Ifat.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Soon after, Ethiopia conquered Damot and the Muslim states, entering into a 'golden age'.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the 16th century Muslims united behind Adal in *jihad* to reconquer the Muslim lands and occupy Ethiopia, until, with Portuguese assistance, Ethiopia counter-attacked and its sovereignty was restored in a reduced state.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The 16th and 17th centuries also saw Oromo invasions into the Horn, weakening Ethiopia further and causing the collapse of Adal, while Ajuran on the east coast also disintegrated.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Ethiopia briefly consolidated its authority in the late-17th century, though the turn of the century saw fragmentation and gradually-increasing anarchy, which continued throughout the 18th century.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the Sahel region of West Africa, the Ghana Empire formed from between the 2nd and 8th centuries, while from the 7th century the Gao Empire ruled to its east.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Almoravid capture of royal Aoudaghost led to Ghana's conversion to Islam in the 11th century, and climatic changes led to Ghana's conquest by its vassal Sosso in the 13th century.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Sosso was quickly overthrown by the Mali Empire who conquered Gao and dominated the trans-Saharan trade.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The Mossi Kingdoms were established to its south.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The 15th century saw the crumbling of the Mali Empire, with the dominant power in the region becoming the Songhai Empire centered on Gao.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Weakened by internal conflict, in 1591 Gao was conquered by Morocco, and the political vacuum came to be filled by the Segou Empire and several other states.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The once lucrative trans-Saharan trade gradually lost its prominence to the coastal Atlantic trade with Europeans, and the following centuries saw many droughts, famines, and epidemics.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the forest regions of West Africa, various kingdoms and empires flourished, such as the Yoruba empires of Ife and Oyo, the Igbo Kingdom of Nri, the Edo Kingdom of Benin (famous for its art), the Dagomba Kingdom of Dagbon, and the Akan kingdoms of Bonoman and Adanse.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] They came into contact with the Portuguese in the 15th century which saw the start of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The Asante Empire was established in present-day Ghana.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Between 1515 and 1800, 8 million Africans were exported in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the western Congo Basin by the 13th century there were three main confederations of states: the Seven Kingdoms, Mpemba, and one led by Vungu.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the 14th century the Kingdom of Kongo emerged and dominated the region, with the Tio Kingdom to its north and Mwene Muji to its northeast.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Over the course of the late-16th and 17th centuries, the Portuguese sought to conquer Ndongo (allied to Matamba) in the Angolan Wars; despite fierce resistance from Queen Nzinga, and brief occupation of Luanda by the Dutch (allied to Kongo), Portugal controlled most of Ndongo by the 1670s.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The late-17th century saw Kongo fragment between royal houses as several vassals broke away; by the time of Kongo's restoration in 1709, it had ceased being the dominant regional power.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Also during the 17th century, in the textile-producing northeast, the Boma, Yaka, and possibly the Kuba and Pende kingdoms broke away from Mwene Muji.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the eastern Congo Basin, farmers, fishermen, and hunters (often Pygmies) built symbiotic relations.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Jan Vansina wrote that in the southern savanna 'lords of the land' held priestly roles due to their special relationship with the spirits of the land, and held sway over multiple villages, effectively ruling embryonic kingdoms.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Accordingly, as lineages grew, authority was opportunistically absorbed or incorporated by force.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The centre of the Luba Empire is yet to undergo archaeological research, meaning knowledge about its rise is limited; its foundation is typically dated to the 14th/15th centuries, though scholarly estimates range from the 8th to 17th centuries.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] A Lunda state formed in the Nkalany Valley (estimates range from c.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] 1700), in the 18th century, Lunda rapidly expanded into an extensive commonwealth across the southern savanna, using the institutions of perpetual kinship and positional succession to incorporate peoples.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Meanwhile, Luba expanded its number of tributaries, in some cases using its widely acknowledged prestige to intervene in succession disputes and distribute ritually-powerful royal regalia related to *bulopwe* (sacred kingship), in other cases using conquest.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the northern Great Lakes, the Empire of Kitara rose around the 11th century, famed for its oral traditions.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Peter Robertshaw considered its rulers (the Chwezi) to have been religious leaders who utilised networks of hill-top shrines to project authority.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Around 1500, severe droughts and famine destabilised the region, occurring again during the early-17th and 18th centuries.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Luo-speaking peoples migrated from the Upper Nile basin into modern-day Uganda, and a Biito dynasty replaced the Chwezi in Bunyoro-Kitara.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Over the following centuries, the kingdoms of Bunyoro-Kitara, Buganda, and Rwanda struggled for hegemony among others.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, Bunyoro raided states to the south such as Nkore and Rwanda.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Mpororo rose and fragmented during the 18th century, while Buganda rapidly expanded at the expense of Bunyoro to become the major power in the region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The East African interior was inhabited by pastoralist Cushitic and Nilotic speakers, along with Bantu speakers who continued to expand and adapt to their lands while absorbing the former two; the 17th century saw the establishment of tributary systems that stabilised the region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] On the Swahili coast the Swahili city-states thrived off of the Indian Ocean trade and gradually Islamized, giving rise to the Kilwa Sultanate from the 10th century.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the 15th century, trade routes for Zimbabwean gold shifted north, weakening Kilwa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The Portuguese arrived at the coast soon after, and exploited divisions between coastal city-states to gain control over them while utilising a powerful navy.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the 17th and 18th centuries, Lamu-Swahili cities rebelled against the Portuguese and allied the Omani Empire which supplanted Portuguese rule.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Madagascar was settled by Austronesian peoples between the 5th and 7th centuries, as societies organized at the behest of *hasina* and competed over with one another over the island's estuaries and bridgeheads.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] From around the 15th century, southern Madagascar became integrated into global trade; the Sakalava Empire rose to dominate west-coastal trade, accompanied by numerous other states, and the island saw several failed European colonial ventures.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In Southern Africa, an early kingdom was Mapungubwe, which collapsed c.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] 1300 as Great Zimbabwe, with its monumental dry-stone walls, rose to become the region's main political and economic centre.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Following shifting trade routes north to the Zambezi and unclear circumstances, Great Zimbabwe entered into decline and was succeeded by the Mutapa Empire and Kingdom of Butua in the 15th century.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Mutapa was briefly vassalised by the Portuguese in the 17th century, the latter-half of which saw widespread famine and disease, until Changamire Dombo revolted in the 1680s, conquered Butua to found the Rozvi Empire, and expelled all Portuguese from the Zimbabwean Plateau.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] North of the Zambezi, Maravi around Lake Malawi expanded in the 17th century, but the collapse of its succession system in the 18th century precipitated its disintegration.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] By the late-1st millennium CE, Bantu-speaking farmers populated most of Southern Africa's cultivable savannas, reaching southwards to the Kei River; they traded goods such as livestock, grain, and metal tools between communities and with hunter-gatherers.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Further south, the Dutch began colonizing the western Cape in the 17th century, and Britain seized control of the colony around the turn of the 19th century.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the late-18th century, the interplay of pre-existing trends of political centralization with the effects of international trade, environmental instability, and European colonisation set the *Mfecane* ("Crushing") in motion, as various African states were founded.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] By the turn of the 19th century, many of Africa's economic and political structures were unstable and brittle as a result of long-term effects of the slave trade.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In Egypt Muhammad Ali led a national movement to seize power from Ottoman suzerainty, instituting sweeping reforms and greatly strengthening Egyptian power by militaristic expansion.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Meanwhile, in West Africa the Fula *jihad*s, which had been gaining momentum throughout the 18th century, culminated in the establishment of the expansive Sokoto and Hamdullahi caliphates.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In the Horn, Ethiopia underwent reforms, seeking to revive the imperial state, something that was later achieved by Menelik II's conquests.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In Southern Africa the *Mfecane* propelled large long-distance migrations that caused widespread disruption across the vast region, while several Boer republics were founded.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] European campaigns to abolish the Atlantic slave trade led to supply refocusing on internal markets and saw the rapid growth of the Indian Ocean slave trade.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Across the continent many rulers attempted reforms and indigenous forms of 'modernisation', however these efforts were consistently undermined by European traders and missionaries as the tide of European encroachment rose.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] For 400 years, European nations had mainly limited their involvement to trading stations on the African coast, with few daring to venture inland.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The Industrial Revolution in Europe produced several technological innovations which assisted them in overcoming this 400-year pattern.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] One was the development of repeating rifles, which were easier and quicker to load than muskets.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Maxim developed the maxim gun, the model of the modern-day machine gun.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] European states kept these weapons largely among themselves by refusing to sell these weapons to African leaders.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] African germs took numerous European lives and deterred permanent settlements.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Diseases such as yellow fever, sleeping sickness, yaws, and leprosy made Africa a very inhospitable place for Europeans.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The deadliest disease was malaria, endemic throughout Tropical Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In 1854, the discovery of quinine and other medical innovations helped to make conquest and colonisation in Africa possible.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] There were strong motives for the conquest of Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Raw materials were needed for European factories, and free trade was championed to prevent Africans from regulating their economies.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Prestige and imperial rivalries were at play.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Acquiring African colonies would show rivals that a nation was powerful and significant.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] These contextual factors forged the Scramble for Africa; during the late-19th and early-20th centuries the European powers partitioned and conquered almost all of Africa despite fierce resistance (only Ethiopia and Liberia remained independent).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Traditional leaders were incorporated into the colonial regimes as a form of indirect rule to extract human and natural resources and curb organized resistance.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Colonial borders were drawn unilaterally by the Europeans, often cutting across bonds of kinship, language, culture, and established routes, and sometimes incorporating groups who previously had little in common.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The threat to trade routes was mitigated by poor policing and African entrepreneurs (viewed as smugglers) who exploited the differing tax and legal schemes.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The first few decades of European colonialism saw intense violence, disorder, and atrocities, such as that of the Congo Free State, German South West Africa, and French Algeria, with the late colonial period relatively peaceful in comparison.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Colonial rule had wide-reaching effects on African societies, such as the spread of Christianity as part of the 'civilising mission'.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] African culture was strongly denigrated and persecuted, as pervasive racial discrimination deepened the scars of humiliation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Imperial rule by Europeans continued until after the conclusion of World War II, when almost all remaining colonial territories gradually obtained formal independence.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Independence movements in Africa gained momentum following World War II, which left the major European powers weakened.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In 1951, Libya, a former Italian colony, gained independence.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In 1956, Tunisia and Morocco won their independence from France.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Ghana followed suit the next year (March 1957), becoming the first of the sub-Saharan colonies to be granted independence.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Over the next decade, waves of decolonisation took place across the continent, culminating in the 1960 Year of Africa and the establishment of the Organisation of African Unity in 1963.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Portugal's overseas presence in sub-Saharan Africa (most notably in Angola, Cape Verde, Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau, and São Tomé and Príncipe) lasted from the 16th century to 1975, after the Estado Novo regime was overthrown in a military coup in Lisbon.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Rhodesia unilaterally declared independence from the United Kingdom in 1965, under the white minority government of Ian Smith, but was not internationally recognised as an independent state (as Zimbabwe) until 1980, when black nationalists gained power after a bitter guerrilla war.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Although South Africa was one of the first African countries to gain independence, the state remained under the control of the country's white minority, initially through qualified voting rights and from 1956 by a system of racial segregation known as apartheid, until 1994.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] As of 2025, Africa contains 54 sovereign countries.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Since independence, African states have frequently been hampered by instability, corruption, violence, and authoritarianism.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The vast majority of African states are republics that operate under some form of the presidential system of rule.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] However, few of them have been able to sustain democratic governments on a permanent basis—per the criteria laid out by Lührmann et al.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] (2018), only Botswana and Mauritius have been consistently democratic for the entirety of their post-colonial history.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Most African countries have experienced several coups or periods of military dictatorship.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Between 1990 and 2018, though, the continent as a whole has trended towards more democratic governance.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Upon independence an overwhelming majority of Africans lived in extreme poverty.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The continent suffered from the lack of infrastructural or industrial development under colonial rule, along with political instability.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] With limited financial resources or access to global markets, relatively stable countries such as Kenya still experienced only very slow economic development.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Only a handful of African countries succeeded in obtaining rapid economic growth prior to 1990.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Exceptions include Libya and Equatorial Guinea, both of which possess large oil reserves.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Instability throughout the continent after decolonisation resulted primarily from marginalisation of ethnic groups, and corruption.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Faced with increasingly frequent and severe violence, military rule was widely accepted by the population of many countries as means to maintain order, and during the 1970s and 1980s a majority of African countries were controlled by military dictatorships.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Territorial disputes between nations and rebellions by groups seeking independence were also common in independent African states.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The most devastating of these was the Nigerian Civil War, fought between government forces and an Igbo separatist republic, which resulted in a famine that killed 1–2 million people.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Two civil wars in Sudan, the first lasting from 1955 to 1972 and the second from 1983 to 2005, collectively killed around 3 million.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Both were fought primarily on ethnic and religious lines.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Cold War conflicts between the United States and the Soviet Union also contributed to instability.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Both the Soviet Union and the United States offered considerable incentives to African political and military leaders who aligned themselves with the superpowers' foreign policy.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] As an example, during the Angolan Civil War, the Soviet and Cuban aligned MPLA and the American aligned UNITA received the vast majority of their military and political support from these countries.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Many African countries became highly dependent on foreign aid.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The sudden loss of both Soviet and American aid at the end of the Cold War and fall of the USSR resulted in severe economic and political turmoil in the countries most dependent on foreign support.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] There was a major famine in Ethiopia between 1983 and 1985, killing up to 1.2 million people, which most historians attribute primarily to the forced relocation of farmworkers and seizure of grain by the communist Derg government, further exacerbated by the civil war.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] In 1994 a genocide in Rwanda resulted in up to 800,000 deaths, added to a severe refugee crisis and fuelled the rise of militia groups in neighbouring countries.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] This contributed to the outbreak of the first and second Congo Wars, which were the most devastating military conflicts in modern Africa, with up to 5.5 million deaths, making it by far the deadliest conflict in modern African history and one of the costliest wars in human history.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Various conflicts between various insurgent groups and governments continue.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Since 2003, there has been an ongoing conflict in Darfur (Sudan), which peaked in intensity from 2003 to 2005 with notable spikes in violence in 2007 and 2013–15, killing around 300,000 people total.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The Boko Haram Insurgency primarily within Nigeria (with considerable fighting in Niger, Chad, and Cameroon as well) has killed around 350,000 people since 2009.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Most African conflicts have been reduced to low-intensity conflicts as of 2022.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] However, the Tigray War from 2020 to 2022 killed an estimated 300,000–500,000 people, primarily due to famine.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Overall though, violence across Africa has greatly declined in the 21st century, with the end of civil wars in Angola, Sierra Leone, and Algeria in 2002, Liberia in 2003, and Sudan and Burundi in 2005.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] The Second Congo War, which involved 9 countries and several insurgent groups, ended in 2003.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] This decline in violence coincided with many countries abandoning communist-style command economies and opening up for market reforms, which over the course of the 1990s and 2000s promoted the establishment of permanent, peaceful trade between neighbouring countries (see Capitalist peace).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Improved stability and economic reforms have led to a great increase in foreign investment into many African nations, mainly from China, which further spurred economic growth.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] Between 2000 and 2014, annual GDP growth in sub-Saharan Africa averaged 5.02%, doubling its total GDP from $811 billion to $1.63 trillion (constant 2015 USD).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] North Africa experienced comparable growth rates.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] A significant part of this growth can also be attributed to the facilitated diffusion of information technologies and specifically the mobile telephone.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p01] While several individual countries have maintained high growth rates, since 2014 overall growth has considerably slowed, primarily as a result of falling commodity prices, continued lack of industrialisation, and epidemics such as Ebola and COVID-19.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Africa is the largest of the three great southward projections from the largest landmass of the Earth.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Separated from Europe by the Mediterranean Sea, it is joined to Asia at its northeast extremity by the Isthmus of Suez (transected by the Suez Canal), 163 km (101 mi) wide.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Geopolitically, Egypt's Sinai Peninsula east of the Suez Canal is often considered part of Africa as well.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The coastline is 26,000 km (16,000 mi) long, and the absence of deep indentations of the shore is illustrated by the fact that Europe, which covers only 10,400,000 km2 (4,000,000 sq mi) – about a third of the surface of Africa – has a coastline of 32,000 km (20,000 mi).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] From the most northerly point, Ras ben Sakka in Tunisia (37°21' N), to the most southerly point, Cape Agulhas in South Africa (34°51'15" S), is a distance of approximately 8,000 km (5,000 mi).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Cape Verde, 17°33'22" W, the westernmost point, is a distance of approximately 7,400 km (4,600 mi) to Ras Hafun, 51°27'52" E, the most easterly projection that neighbours Cape Guardafui, the tip of the Horn of Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Africa's largest country is Algeria, and its smallest country is Seychelles, an archipelago off the east coast.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The smallest nation on the continental mainland is The Gambia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The African plate, also known as the Nubian plate, is a major tectonic plate that includes most of the continent of Africa (except for its easternmost part) and the adjacent oceanic crust to the west and south.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] It also includes a narrow strip of Western Asia along the Mediterranean Sea, including much of Israel, Palestine and Lebanon.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] It is bounded by the North American plate and South American plate to the west (separated by the Mid-Atlantic Ridge); the Arabian plate and Somali plate to the east; the Eurasian plate, Aegean Sea plate and Anatolian plate to the north; and the Antarctic plate to the south.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Between 60 million years ago and 10 million years ago, the Somali plate began rifting from the African plate along the East African Rift.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Since the continent of Africa consists of crust from both the African and the Somali plates, some literature refers to the African plate as the *Nubian plate* to distinguish it from the continent as a whole.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The climate of Africa ranges from tropical to subarctic on its highest peaks.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Its northern half is primarily desert, or arid, while its central and southern areas contain both savanna plains and dense jungle (rainforest) regions.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In between, there is a convergence, where vegetation patterns such as sahel and steppe dominate.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Africa is the hottest continent on Earth and 60% of the entire land surface consists of drylands and deserts.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The record for the highest-ever recorded temperature, in Libya in 1922 (58 °C (136 °F)), was discredited in 2013.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Climate change in Africa is a serious threat because the continent is one of the most vulnerable regions to the effects of climate change, despite being responsible for less than 4% of global greenhouse emissions.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Climate change is causing increasingly erratic rainfall patterns, more frequent extreme weather events such as droughts, floods, and rising sea-surface temperatures across the continent.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] These changes threaten food and water security, biodiversity, public health, and economic development.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Africa is currently warming faster than the rest of the world on average.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Climate change intensifies existing socioeconomic vulnerabilities.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Large segments of the African population depend on climate-sensitive livelihoods such as agriculture (55 - 62% of the workforce in sub-Saharan Africa) and already live in poverty, heightening their exposure to shocks.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Health outcomes worsen as heat stress, vector-borne diseases (such as malaria and dengue), and malnutrition become more prevalent.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Over half (56%) of the over 2,000 recorded public health incidents in Africa between 2001 and 2021 were connected to climate change.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Resource scarcity contributes to displacement and conflict, particularly in fragile regions.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Urban areas, often characterized by informal settlements, face heightened risks from flooding and extreme heat.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Africa has over 3,000 protected areas, with 198 marine protected areas, 50 biosphere reserves, and 80 wetlands reserves.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Significant habitat destruction, increases in human population and poaching are reducing Africa's biological diversity and arable land.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Human encroachment, civil unrest and the introduction of non-native species threaten biodiversity in Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] This has been exacerbated by administrative problems, inadequate personnel and funding problems.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Deforestation is affecting Africa at twice the world rate, according to the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The deforestation rate of 4.08 million hectares in 2000–2015 declined to 3.45 million ha per year in 2015–2025.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Some sources claim that approximately 90% of the original, virgin forests in West Africa have been destroyed.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Over 90% of Madagascar's original forests have been destroyed since the arrival of humans 2000 years ago.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] About 65% of Africa's agricultural land suffers from soil degradation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] It is also home to a variety of "jungle" animals including snakes and primates and aquatic life such as crocodiles and amphibians.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In addition, Africa has the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] African environmental problems are problems caused by the direct and indirect human impacts on the natural environment and affect humans and nearly all forms of life in Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Issues include deforestation, soil degradation, air pollution, water pollution, coastal erosion, garbage pollution, climate change, Oil spills, Biodiversity loss, and water scarcity (resulting in problems with access to safe water supply and sanitation).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] These issues result in environmental conflict and are connected to broader social struggles for democracy and sovereignty.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The scarcity of climate adaptation techniques in Africa makes it the least resilient continent to climate change.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The African Union (AU) is a continental union consisting of 55 member states.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The union was formed, with Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, as its headquarters, on 26 June 2001.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The union was officially established on 9 July 2002 as a successor to the Organisation of African Unity (OAU).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In July 2004, the African Union's Pan-African Parliament (PAP) was relocated to Midrand, in South Africa, but the African Commission on Human and Peoples' Rights remained in Addis Ababa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The African Union, not to be confused with the AU Commission, is formed by the Constitutive Act of the African Union, which aims to transform the African Economic Community, a federated commonwealth, into a state under established international conventions.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The African Union has a parliamentary government, known as the African Union Government, consisting of legislative, judicial and executive organs.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] It is led by the African Union President and Head of State, who is also the President of the Pan-African Parliament.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] A person becomes AU President by being elected to the PAP, and subsequently gaining majority support in the PAP.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The government of the AU consists of all-union, regional, state, and municipal authorities, as well as hundreds of institutions, that together manage the day-to-day affairs of the institution.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Extensive human rights abuses still occur in several parts of Africa, often under the oversight of the state.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Most of such violations occur for political reasons, often as a side effect of civil war.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Countries where major human rights violations have been reported in recent times include the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Sierra Leone, Liberia, Sudan, Zimbabwe, and Ivory Coast.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] African nations have made great efforts to respect international borders as inviolate for a long time.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] For example, the Organization of African Unity (OAU), which was established in 1963 and replaced by the African Union in 2002, set the respect for the territorial integrity of each country as one of its principles in OAU Charter.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Indeed, compared with the formation of European countries, there have been fewer international conflicts in Africa for changing the borders, which has influenced country formation there and has enabled some countries to survive that might have been defeated and absorbed by others.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Yet international conflicts have played out by support for proxy armies or rebel movements.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Many states have experienced civil wars: including Rwanda, Sudan, Angola, Sierra Leone, Congo, Liberia, Ethiopia and Somalia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Wars of national liberation also often took up a Marxist, Marxist–Leninist, or Maoist character in ideological terms, where the independence of African nations was raised in Marxian terms.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Early examples included the Union of the Peoples of Cameroon armed movement against French colonialism, a Marxist–Leninist insurgency, followed by similar movements in Congo (the Simba Rebellion).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Che Guevara participated in the latter, and opined in 1967 that Africa was not ready for revolution.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Despite this, in Zanzibar before and after unification with Tanzania, forms of socialism took hold.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Even after 1990, there are some examples of Military Marxism, such as a militia established by Ernest Wamba-dia-Wamba in Eastern Congo in the 1990s.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The countries in this table are categorised according to the scheme for geographic subregions used by the United Nations, and data included are per sources in cross-referenced articles.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Where they differ, provisos are clearly indicated.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] This list contains nine territories that are administered as incorporated areas of a primarily non-African country but that belong geographically to the African continent.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The continent's total nominal GDP remains behind that of several individual countries, including the United States, China, Japan, Germany, the United Kingdom, India and France.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] According to the United Nations' Human Development Report in 2003, the bottom 24 ranked nations (151st to 175th) were all African.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Poverty, illiteracy, malnutrition, inadequate water supply and sanitation, and poor health affect a large proportion of the people who reside on the African continent.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In August 2008, the World Bank announced revised global poverty estimates based on a new international poverty line of $1.25 per day (versus the previous measure of $1.00).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Eighty-one percent of the sub-Saharan African population was living on less than $2.50 (PPP) per day in 2005, compared with 86% for India.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa is the least successful region of the world in reducing poverty ($1.25 per day); some 50% of the population living in poverty in 1981 (200 million people), a figure that rose to 58% in 1996 before dropping to 50% in 2005 (380 million people).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The average poor person in sub-Saharan Africa is estimated to live on only 70 cents per day, and was poorer in 2003 than in 1973, indicating increasing poverty in some areas.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Some of it is attributed to unsuccessful economic liberalisation programmes spearheaded by foreign companies and governments, but other studies have cited bad domestic government policies more than external factors.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Africa is now at risk of being in debt once again, particularly in sub-Saharan African countries.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The last debt crisis in 2005 was resolved with help from the heavily indebted poor countries scheme (HIPC).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The HIPC resulted in some positive and negative effects on the economy in Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] About ten years after the 2005 debt crisis in sub-Saharan Africa was resolved, Zambia fell back into debt.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] A small reason was due to the fall in copper prices in 2011, but the bigger reason was that a large amount of the money Zambia borrowed was wasted or pocketed by the elite.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] From 1995 to 2005, Africa's rate of economic growth increased, averaging 5% in 2005.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Some countries experienced still higher growth rates, notably Angola, Sudan and Equatorial Guinea, all of which had recently begun extracting their petroleum reserves or had expanded their oil extraction capacity.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The following table shows the projected nominal GDP and GDP per capita (at purchasing power parity) in 2026 by the IMF.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The continent is believed to hold 90% of the world's cobalt, 90% of its platinum, 50% of its gold, 98% of its chromium, 70% of its tantalite, 64% of its manganese and one-third of its uranium.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) has 70% of the world's coltan, a mineral used in the production of tantalum capacitors for electronic devices such as cell phones.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The DRC also has more than 30% of the world's diamond reserves.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Guinea is the world's largest exporter of bauxite.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] As the growth in Africa has been driven mainly by services and not manufacturing or agriculture, it has been growth without jobs and without reduction in poverty levels.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In fact, the food security crisis of 2008, which took place following the global financial crisis, pushed 100 million people into food insecurity.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In 2024 nearly 307 million people in Africa were undernourished (46% of the global total), an increase of 10 million people since 2023 and 34 million from 2022.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In recent years, China has built increasingly stronger ties with African nations and is Africa's largest trading partner.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In 2007, Chinese companies invested a total of US$1 billion in Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] A Harvard University study led by professor Calestous Juma showed that Africa could feed itself by making the transition from importer to self-sufficiency.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] "African agriculture is at the crossroads; we have come to the end of a century of policies that favoured Africa's export of raw materials and importation of food.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Cooking with biogas in Tanzania; Geothermal energy infrastructure in Kenya; Coal power station in South Africa; Solar-powered lamp-light in Zambia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Energy in Africa is characterised by low per-capita consumption and limited access to modern energy services, reflecting both infrastructural and socio-economic challenges across the continent.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] As of 2023, Africa accounted for just 5.5% of global total final energy consumption, with per-capita energy use more than three times lower than the global average.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The energy mix is dominated by biofuels and waste, which make up 43% of total final consumption, primarily for household cooking and heating, followed by oil products at 33%, electricity at 11%, natural gas at 9%, and coal at 4%.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Electricity access remains a major challenge, particularly in Sub-Saharan Africa, where nearly 450 million rural residents lack reliable electricity, and grid coverage is often inconsistent.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Clean cooking solutions are similarly underdeveloped, leaving over 900 million people reliant on polluting fuels such as firewood, charcoal, and agricultural residues, which disproportionately affect women and children.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Transport energy is dominated by oil products, reflecting low motorisation rates and limited adoption of electric mobility, although countries such as Ethiopia, Morocco, and Egypt have begun adopting policies to reduce fossil fuel dependency.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Africa possesses some of the world's most abundant energy resources, including oil, natural gas, coal, hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and biomass, much of which remains underutilised.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] While fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and natural gas continue to dominate energy production and electricity generation in Africa, renewable sources are increasingly expanding across the continent.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and modern biomass are growing in capacity, though their deployment remains uneven and limited compared to the continent's vast potential.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Hydropower is the largest non-combustible renewable source, while solar energy offers immense potential due to high irradiation levels, particularly in the Sahara and Sahel.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] There are regional differences: North Africa is dominated by oil and gas production, Southern Africa by coal and hydropower, East Africa by hydropower and geothermal, and West and Central Africa face major electrification gaps despite hydroelectric potential.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Water development and management are complex in Africa due to the multiplicity of trans-boundary water resources (rivers, lakes and aquifers).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Around 75% of sub-Saharan Africa falls within 53 international river basin catchments that traverse multiple borders.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] This particular constraint can also be converted into an opportunity if the potential for trans-boundary cooperation is harnessed in the development of the area's water resources.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] A multi-sectoral analysis of the Zambezi River, for example, shows that riparian cooperation could lead to a 23% increase in firm energy production without any additional investments.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] A number of institutional and legal frameworks for transboundary cooperation exist, such as the Zambezi River Authority, the Southern African Development Community (SADC) Protocol, Volta River Authority and the Nile Basin Commission.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] However, additional efforts are required to further develop political will, as well as the financial capacities and institutional frameworks needed for win-win multilateral cooperative actions and optimal solutions for all riparians.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Africa is considered by anthropologists to be the most genetically diverse continent as a result of being the longest inhabited.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Africa's population has rapidly increased over the last 40 years, and is consequently relatively young.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In some African states, more than half the population is under 25 years of age.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The total number of people in Africa increased from 229 million in 1950 to 630 million in 1990.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] As of 2021, the population of Africa is estimated at 1,394 million.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Africa's total population surpassing other continents is fairly recent; African population surpassed Europe in the 1990s, while the Americas was overtaken sometime around the year 2000.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] This increase in number of babies born in Africa compared to the rest of the world is expected to reach approximately 37% in the year 2050; while in 1990 sub-Saharan Africa accounted for only 16% of the world's births.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The total fertility rate (children per woman) for Sub-Saharan Africa is 4.7 as of 2018, the highest in the world.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] All countries in sub-Saharan Africa had TFRs (average number of children) above replacement level in 2019 and accounted for 27.1% of global livebirths.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In 2021, sub-Saharan Africa accounted for 29% of global births.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Speakers of Bantu languages (part of the Niger–Congo family) are the majority in southern, central and southeast Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The Bantu-speaking peoples from the Sahel progressively expanded over most of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] But there are also several Nilotic groups in South Sudan and East Africa, the mixed Swahili people on the Swahili Coast, and a few remaining indigenous Khoisan ("San" or "Bushmen") and Pygmy peoples in Southern and Central Africa, respectively.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Bantu-speaking Africans also predominate in Gabon and Equatorial Guinea, and are found in parts of southern Cameroon.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In the Kalahari Desert of Southern Africa, the distinct people known as the Bushmen (also "San", closely related to, but distinct from "Hottentots") have long been present.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The San are physically distinct from other Africans and are the indigenous people of southern Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Pygmies are the pre-Bantu indigenous peoples of central Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The peoples of West Africa primarily speak Niger–Congo languages, belonging mostly to its non-Bantu branches, though some Nilo-Saharan and Afro-Asiatic speaking groups are also found.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The Niger–Congo-speaking Yoruba, Igbo, Fulani, Akan, and Wolof ethnic groups are the largest and most influential.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In the central Sahara, Mandinka or Mande groups are most significant.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Chadic-speaking groups, including the Hausa, are found in more northerly parts of the region nearest to the Sahara, and Nilo-Saharan communities, such as the Songhai, Kanuri, and Zarma, are found in the eastern parts of West Africa bordering Central Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The peoples of North Africa consist of three main indigenous groups: Berbers in the northwest, Egyptians in the northeast, and Nilo-Saharan-speaking peoples in the east.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The Arabs who arrived in the 7th century AD introduced the Arabic language and Islam to North Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The Semitic Phoenicians (who founded Carthage) and Hyksos, the Indo-Iranian Alans, the Indo-European Greeks, Romans, and Vandals settled in North Africa as well.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Significant Berber communities remain within Morocco and Algeria in the 21st century, while, to a lesser extent, Berber speakers are also present in some regions of Tunisia and Libya.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The Berber-speaking Tuareg and other often-nomadic peoples are the principal inhabitants of the Saharan interior of North Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In Mauritania, there is a small but near-extinct Berber community in the north and Niger–Congo-speaking peoples in the south, though in both regions Arabic and Arab culture predominates.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In Sudan, although Arabic and Arab culture predominate, it is mostly inhabited by groups that originally spoke Nilo-Saharan, such as the Nubians, Fur, Masalit and Zaghawa, who, over the centuries, have variously intermixed with migrants from the Arabian peninsula.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Small communities of Afro-Asiatic-speaking Beja nomads can also be found in Egypt and Sudan.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In the Horn of Africa, some Ethiopian and Eritrean groups (like the Amhara and Tigrayans, collectively known as Habesha) speak languages from the Semitic branch of the Afro-Asiatic language family, while the Oromo and Somali speak languages from the Cushitic branch of Afro-Asiatic.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Prior to the decolonisation movements of the post-World War II era, Europeans were represented in every part of Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Decolonization during the 1960s and 1970s often resulted in the mass emigration of white settlers—especially from Algeria and Morocco (1.6 million *pieds-noirs* in North Africa), Kenya, Congo, Rhodesia, Mozambique and Angola.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Between 1975 and 1977, over a million colonials returned to Portugal alone.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Nevertheless, white Africans remain an important minority in many African states, particularly Zimbabwe, Namibia, Réunion, and South Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The country with the largest white African population is South Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Dutch and British diasporas represent the largest communities of European ancestry on the continent today.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] European colonisation also brought sizable groups of Asians, particularly from the Indian subcontinent, to British colonies.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Large Indian communities are found in South Africa, and smaller ones are present in Kenya, Tanzania, and some other southern and southeast African countries.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The large Indian community in Uganda was expelled by the dictator Idi Amin in 1972, though many have since returned.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The islands in the Indian Ocean are also populated primarily by people of Asian origin, often mixed with Africans and Europeans.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The Malagasy people of Madagascar are an Austronesian people, but those along the coast are generally mixed with Bantu, Arab, Indian and European origins.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Malay and Indian ancestries are also important components in the group of people known in South Africa as Cape Coloureds (people with origins in two or more races and continents).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] During the 20th century, small but economically important communities of Lebanese have also developed in the larger coastal cities of West and East Africa, respectively.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The Sahara served as a trans-regional passageway and place of dwelling for people in Africa during various humid phases and periods throughout the history of Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] As early as 11,000 years ago, Sub-Saharan West Africans, bearing macrohaplogroup L (e.g., L1b1a11, L1b1a6a, L1b1a8, L1b1a9a1, L2a1k, L3d1b1a), may have migrated through North Africa and into Europe, mostly into southern Europe (e.g., Iberia).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The genetic marker E1b1 was identified to have wide distribution across Egypt, with "P2/215/M35.1 (E1b1b), for short M35, likely also originated in eastern tropical Africa, and is predominantly distributed in an arc from the Horn of Africa up through Egypt".
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The R haplogroup has also been identified to have high frequencies in central Saharan Africa, among some Afro-Asiatic and Nilo-Saharan language speaking groups.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Genetic evidence has identified the Horn of Africa to be the source of a genetic marker "M35/215" Y-chromosome lineage for a significant population component which moved north from that region into Egypt and the Levant.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Historian Christopher Ehret argued that this genetic distribution paralleled the spread of the Afrasian language family with the movement of people from the Horn of Africa into Egypt and added a new demic component to the existing population of Egypt 17,000 years ago.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] According to a recent study, the Arab migrations to the Maghreb was mainly a demographic process that heavily implied gene flow and remodelled the genetic structure of the Maghreb region in North Africa, rather than a mere cultural replacement as claimed by older studies.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Another study found out that the majority of J-M267 (Eu10) chromosomes in the Maghreb are due to the recent gene flow caused by the Arab migrations to the Maghreb in the first millennium CE as both southern Qahtanite and northern Adnanite Arabs added to the heterogenous Maghrebi ethnic melting pot.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The Eu10 chromosome pool in the Maghreb is derived not only from early Neolithic dispersions from Western Asia but to a much greater extent from recent expansions of Arab tribes from the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] David Schoenbrun, Christopher Ehret, Steven A.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Brandt and Shomarka Keita (2025) have highlighted the problematic categorisation of genetic haplogroups characterised as ‘African’ and ‘Eurasian' in North African genome studies.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In reference to the van de Loosdrecht et al.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In their view, identifying a range of African populations may still remain an issue “since the idea of ‘African’ still gets stereotyped or restricted.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] (Accepting the southwestern Asian/Levantine geographical continuity with Africa eliminates a conceptual barrier related to racio-typological thinking permitting an Africasian construct analogous to Eurasian.)”.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] While Africans profess a wide variety of religious beliefs, the majority of the people respect African religions or parts of them.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] However, in formal surveys or census, most people will identify with major religions that came from outside the continent, mainly through colonisation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] There are several reasons for this, the main one being the colonial idea that African religious beliefs and practices are not good enough.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Religious beliefs and statistics on religious affiliation are difficult to come by since they are often a sensitive topic for governments with mixed religious populations.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] According to the *World Book Encyclopedia*, Islam and Christianity are the two largest religions in Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Islam is most prevalent in Northern Africa, and is the state religion of many North African countries, such as Algeria, where 99% of the population practices Islam.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The majority of people in most governments in Southern, Southeast, and Central Africa, as well as in a sizable portion of the Horn of Africa and West Africa, identify as Christians.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] The Coptic Christians constitute a sizable minority in Egypt, and the Ethiopian Orthodox Church is the largest church in Ethiopia, with 36 million and 51 million adherents.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] According to Encyclopædia Britannica, 45% of the population are Christians, 40% are Muslims, and 10% follow traditional religions.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] A small number of Africans are Hindu, Buddhist, Confucianist, Baháʼí, or Jewish.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] There is also a minority of people in Africa who are irreligious.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] By most estimates, well over a thousand languages (UNESCO has estimated around two thousand) are spoken in Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Most are of African origin, though some are of European or Asian origin.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Africa is the most multilingual continent in the world, and it is not rare for individuals to fluently speak not only multiple African languages, but one or more European ones as well.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Following the end of colonialism, nearly all African countries adopted official languages that originated outside the continent, although several countries also granted legal recognition to indigenous languages (such as Swahili, Yoruba, Igbo and Hausa).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In numerous countries, English and French (*see African French*) are used for communication in the public sphere such as government, commerce, education and the media.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Arabic, Portuguese, Afrikaans and Spanish are examples of languages that trace their origin to outside of Africa, and that are used by millions of Africans today, both in the public and private spheres.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Italian is spoken by some in former Italian colonies in Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] German is spoken in Namibia, as it was a former German protectorate.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In total, at least a fifth of Africans speak the former colonial languages.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Moreover, in recent years some African countries have been considering removing their official former colonial languages, such as Mali, Burkina Faso and Niger which removed French as an official language in the 2020s in favour of native languages, while also renaming colonial street names.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] More than 85% of individuals in Africa use traditional medicine as an alternative to often expensive allopathic medical health care and costly pharmaceutical products.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] AIDS in post-colonial Africa is a prevalent issue.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Although the continent is home to about 15.2 percent of the world's population, more than two-thirds of the total infected worldwide—some 35 million people—were Africans, of whom 15 million have already died.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa alone accounted for an estimated 69 percent of all people living with HIV and 70 percent of all AIDS deaths in 2011.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] In the countries of sub-Saharan Africa most affected, AIDS has raised death rates and lowered life expectancy among adults between the ages of 20 and 49 by about twenty years.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p02] Furthermore, the life expectancy in many parts of Africa has declined, largely as a result of the HIV/AIDS epidemic with life-expectancy in some countries reaching as low as thirty-four years.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Africa is divided into a great number of ethnic cultures.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] In recent times, the call for a much greater emphasis on the cultural dimension in all aspects of development has become increasingly vocal.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Some aspects of traditional African cultures have become less practised in recent years as a result of neglect and suppression by colonial and post-colonial regimes.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] For example, African customs were discouraged, and African languages were prohibited in mission schools, while colonialists such as Leopold II of Belgium attempted to "civilize" Africans by discouraging polygamy and witchcraft.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Abiola Irele and Simon Gikandi comment that the current identity of African literature had its genesis in the "traumatic encounter between Africa and Europe".
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] On the other hand, Mhoze Chikowero believes that Africans deployed music, dance, spirituality, and other performative cultures to (re)assert themselves as active agents and indigenous intellectuals, to unmake their colonial marginalisation and reshape their own destinies.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] As of March 2023, 98 African properties are listed by UNESCO as World Heritage Sites.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Among these proprieties, 54 are cultural sites, 39 are natural sites and 5 are mixed sites.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] The List of World Heritage in Danger includes 15 African sites.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] African art refers to works of visual art, including works of sculpture, painting, metalwork, and pottery, originating from the various peoples of the African continent and influenced by distinct, indigenous traditions of aesthetic expression.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] While the various artistic traditions of such a large and diverse continent display considerable regional and cultural variety, there are consistent artistic themes, recurring motifs, and unifying elements across the broad spectrum of the African visual expression.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] As is the case for every artistic tradition in human history, African art was created within specific social, political, and religious contexts.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Likewise, African art was often created not purely for art's sake, but rather with some practical, spiritual, and/or didactic purpose in mind.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] In general, African art prioritizes conceptual and symbolic representation over realism, aiming to visualize the subject's spiritual essence.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Ethiopian art, heavily influenced by Ethiopia's long-standing Christian tradition, is also different from most African art, where Traditional African religion (with Islam prevalent in the north east and north west presently) was dominant until the 20th century.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] African art includes prehistoric and ancient art, the Islamic art of West Africa, the Christian art of East Africa, and the traditional artifacts of these and other regions.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Many African sculptures were historically made of wood and other natural materials that have not survived from earlier than a few centuries ago, although rare older pottery and metal figures can be found in some areas.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Some of the earliest decorative objects, such as shell beads and evidence of paint, have been discovered in Africa, dating to the Middle Stone Age.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Masks are important elements in the art of many people, along with human figures, and are often highly stylized.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] There exist diverse styles, which can often be observed within a single context of origin and may be influenced by the intended use of the object.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Nevertheless, broad regional trends are discernible.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Sculpture is most common among "groups of settled cultivators in the areas drained by the Niger and Congo rivers" in West Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Direct images of deities are relatively infrequent, but masks in particular are or were often made for ritual ceremonies.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Since the late 19th century, there has been an increasing amount of African art in Western collections, the finest pieces of which are displayed as part of the history of colonization.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] African art had an important influence on European Modernist art, which was inspired by their interest in abstract depiction.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] It was this appreciation of African sculpture that has been attributed to the very concept of "African art", as seen by European and American artists and art historians.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Obidoh Freeborn posits that colonialism is one element that has created the character of modern African art.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] According to authors Douglas Fraser and Herbert M.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Author Chika Okeke-Agulu states that "the racist infrastructure of British imperial enterprise forced upon the political and cultural guardians of empire a denial and suppression of an emergent sovereign Africa and modernist art".
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] scaling: small parts of the structure tend to look similar to larger parts, such as a circular village made of circular houses.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] African architecture in some areas has been influenced by external cultures for centuries, according to available evidence.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Western architecture has influenced coastal areas since the late 15th century and is now an important source of inspiration for many larger buildings, particularly in major cities.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] African architecture uses a wide range of materials, including thatch, stick/wood, mud, mudbrick, rammed earth, and stone.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] These material preferences vary by region: North Africa for stone and rammed earth, the Horn of Africa for stone and mortar, West Africa for mud/adobe, Central Africa for thatch/wood and more perishable materials, Southeast and Southern Africa for stone and thatch/wood.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Cinema of Africa refers to the film industries and films produced in the continent of Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] It covers both the history and present of the making or screening of films on the African continent, and also refers to the persons involved in this form of audiovisual culture.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] It dates back to the late 19th century, when film reels were the primary cinematic technology in use.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Cairo has been the capital of film industry in Africa since the early 20th century to the present day.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] As there are more than 50 countries with audiovisual traditions, there is no one single 'African cinema'.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Both historically and culturally, there are major regional differences between North African and sub-Saharan cinemas, and between the cinemas of different countries.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] The Egyptian film industry and the Tunisian are also among the oldest in the world.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Cinema of Egypt in particular is the most established and flourishing industry in Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Pioneers Auguste and Louis Lumière screened their films in Alexandria, Cairo, Tunis, Susa, Libya and Hammam-Lif, Tunisia in 1896.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Albert Samama Chikly is often cited as the first producer of indigenous African cinema, screening his own short documentaries in the casino of Tunis as early as December 1905.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] The continent of Africa and its music is vast and highly diverse, with different regions and nations maintaining distinct musical traditions.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] African music includes genres such as makwaya, highlife, mbube, township music, jùjú, fuji, jaiva, afrobeat, afrofusion, mbalax, Congolese rumba, soukous, ndombolo, makossa, kizomba, and taarab, among others.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] African music also uses a wide variety of instruments from across the continent.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] The music and dance traditions of the African diaspora, shaped to varying degrees by African musical traditions, include American genres such as Dixieland jazz, blues, and jazz, as well as Caribbean styles such as calypso (see kaiso), and soca.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Latin American music genres including cumbia, salsa, son cubano, rumba, conga, bomba, samba, and zouk developed from the music of enslaved Africans and have, in turn, influenced contemporary African popular music.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] African dance (also Afro dance, Afrodance and Afro-dance) refers to the various dance styles of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] These dances are closely connected with the traditional rhythms and music traditions of the region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Music and dancing is an integral part of many traditional African societies.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Songs and dances facilitate teaching and promoting social values, the celebration of special events and major life milestones, the performance of oral history and other recitations, and spiritual experiences.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] African dance uses the concepts of polyrhythm and total body articulation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] African dances are often a collective activity performed in large groups, with significant interaction between dancers and onlookers.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Fifty-four African countries have football teams in the Confederation of African Football.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Egypt has won the African Cup seven times, and a record-making three times in a row.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Cameroon, Nigeria, Morocco, Senegal, Ghana, and Algeria have advanced to the knockout stage of recent FIFA World Cups.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Morocco, at the 2022 World Cup in Qatar was the first African nation to reach the semi-finals of the FIFA Men's World Cup.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] South Africa hosted the 2010 World Cup tournament, becoming the first African country to do so.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] The top clubs in each African football league play the CAF Champions League, while lower-ranked clubs compete in CAF Confederation Cup.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] In recent years, the continent has progressed in terms of state-of-the-art basketball facilities, which have been built in cities such as Cairo, Dakar, Johannesburg, Kigali, Luanda, and Rades.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] The number of African basketball players who drafted into the U.S.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] NBA has experienced growth in the 2010s.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Cricket is popular in some African nations.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] South Africa and Zimbabwe have Test status, while Kenya is the leading non-test team and previously had One-Day International cricket (ODI) status (from 10 October 1997, until 30 January 2014).
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] The three countries jointly hosted the 2003 Cricket World Cup.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Namibia is the other African country to have played in a World Cup.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Morocco, in northern Africa, hosted the 2002 Morocco Cup, but the national team has never qualified for a major tournament.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Rugby is popular in several southern African nations.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Namibia and Zimbabwe have appeared on multiple occasions at the Rugby World Cup, while South Africa is the most successful national team at the Rugby World Cup, having won the tournament on four occasions, in 1995, 2007, 2019, and 2023.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Traditional sports were strictly marginalised during the colonial era, and many are dying or have gone extinct under the pressure of modernisation, however lots remain popular despite not having formal governmental recognition or support.
[src:amazon-rainforest/africa-p03] Some examples are Senegalese wrestling, Dambe, Nguni stick-fighting, and Savika.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The **African Great Lakes** (Swahili: *Maziwa Makuu*; Kinyarwanda: *Ibiyaga bigari*) are a series of lakes constituting the part of the Rift Valley lakes in and around the East African Rift.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Collectively, they contain 31,000 km3 (7,400 mi3) of water, which is more than either Lake Baikal or the North American Great Lakes.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] This total constitutes about 25% of the planet's unfrozen surface fresh water.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The large rift lakes of Africa are the ancient home of great biodiversity, and 10% of the world's fish species live in this region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Countries in the area which are bounded by the lakes of the Great Lakes region include Burundi, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ethiopia, Kenya, Malawi, Mozambique, Rwanda, Tanzania, Uganda and Zambia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The following are included on most lists of the African Great Lakes, grouped by drainage basin.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The exact number of lakes considered part of the African Great Lakes varies by list, and may include smaller lakes in the rift valleys, especially if they are part of the same drainage basin as the larger lakes, such as Lake Kyoga.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The Great Lakes region (rarely: *Greater* Lakes region) consists of ten riparian countries: Burundi, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Ethiopia, Kenya, Malawi, Mozambique, Rwanda, Tanzania, Uganda, and Zambia.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The adjective *interlacustrine* ("between lakes") can refer to the region, or more specifically, the nations or area bounded by the lakes.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The Swahili language is the most commonly spoken language in the African Great Lakes region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] It also serves as a national or official language of five nations in the region: Tanzania, Kenya, Uganda, Rwanda, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Because of its high population—estimated to be more than 50 million people in 2020—and the agricultural surplus in the region, the area became organized into a number of small states.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The most powerful of these monarchies were Buganda, Bunyoro, Karagwe, Rwanda, and Burundi.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Being the long-sought source of the Nile and the watershed triple point between the rivers Nile, Congo and Zambezi, the region had long been of interest to Europeans.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The first Europeans to arrive in the region in any numbers were Christian missionaries who had limited success in converting the locals, but did open the region to later colonization.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Increased contact with the rest of the world led to a series of devastating epidemics affecting both humans and livestock.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] While seen as a region with great potential after independence, the Great Lakes region has suffered from civil war and conflict in the four decades around the turn of the 21st century (c.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] In 2022, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees commended Tanzania for consistently welcoming and aiding refugees from other countries in the region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The highlands are relatively cool, with average temperatures ranging between 17 °C (63 °F) and 19 °C (66 °F) and abundant rainfall.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Major drainage basins include those of the Congo-Zaire, Nile, and Zambezi rivers, which drain into the Atlantic Ocean, Mediterranean Sea, and Indian Ocean, respectively.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Forests are dominant in the lowlands of the Congo-Zaire Basin, while grasslands and savannas (dry grasslands) are most common in the southern and eastern highlands.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Temperatures in the lowlands average about 35 °C (95 °F).
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Around Lake Turkana, the climate is hot and very dry.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] A short rainy season in October is followed by a longer one from April to May.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The Western Rift Valley lakes are freshwater and home to an extraordinary number of endemic species.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] More than 1,500 cichlid fish species live in the lakes, as well as other fish families.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The lakes are also important habitats for a number of amphibian species.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Mammals include elephants, gorillas and hippopotamus.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The Lake Turkana area is home to hundreds of species of birds endemic to Kenya.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The East African rift system also serves as a flyway for migrating birds, bringing in hundreds more.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The birds are essentially supported by plankton masses in the lake, which also feed the fish there.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Vegetation ranges from rainforest to savanna grasses.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] In some lakes, rapidly growing invasive plants, like the surface-choking water hyacinth and shore-clogging papyrus, are problems.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Water hyacinth have thus far affected only Lake Victoria.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Until 12 million years ago, the bountiful waters of the equatorial plateau either flowed west into the Congo River system or east to the Indian Ocean.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] This was changed by the formation of the Great Rift Valley.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] A rift is a weak place in Earth's crust due to the separation of two tectonic plates, often accompanied by a graben, or trough, in which lake water can collect.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] This rift began when East Africa, impelled by currents in the mantle, began separating from the rest of Africa, moving to the northeast.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The basins that resulted from the geological uplifts filled with water that now flowed north.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Lake Victoria is not actually within the Rift Valley.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] It occupies a depression between the Eastern and Western Rifts, formed by the uplift of the rifts to either of its sides.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Around two to three million years ago, Lake Turkana was larger and the area more fertile, making it a center for early hominids.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Richard Leakey led numerous anthropological excavations in the area, which yielded many important discoveries of hominin remains.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The two-million-year-old Skull 1470 was found in 1972.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] It was originally thought to be *Homo habilis*, but some anthropologists have assigned it to a new species, *Homo rudolfensis*, named after the lake (previously known as Lake Rudolf).
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] In 1984, the Turkana Boy, a nearly complete skeleton of a *Homo erectus* boy was discovered.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] In 1999, a 3,500,000-year-old skull was discovered there, named *Kenyanthropus platyops*, which means "flat-faced man of Kenya".
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] Fishing—primarily of tilapia species but also of Nile perch—provides the main livelihood for people in the region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] With four Great Lakes on its borders, Uganda ranks as one of the world's largest producers of freshwater fish.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The climate and rich volcanic soils in the highlands also sustain intensely cultivated croplands.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The economies of the Great Lakes region states have different structures and are at various stages of development.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] The GDP real growth rate ranges from 1.8 percent in Burundi to 4.4 in the DRC.
[src:amazon-rainforest/african-great-lakes] GDP per capita fluctuates between $600 in DRC and Burundi and $800 in Uganda.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] The **Amazon rainforest**, also called the **Amazon jungle**, **Amazonia**, or simply the **Amazon**, is a moist broadleaf tropical rainforest in the Amazon biome that covers most of the Amazon basin of South America.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] This basin encompasses 7 million km2 (2.7 million sq mi), of which 6 million km2 (2.3 million sq mi) are covered by the rainforest.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] This region includes territory belonging to nine nations and 3,344 indigenous territories.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] The majority of the forest, 60%, is in Brazil, followed by Peru with 13%, Colombia with 10%, and with minor amounts in Bolivia, Ecuador, French Guiana, Guyana, Suriname, and Venezuela.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] Four nations have "Amazonas" as the name of one of their first-level administrative regions, and France uses the name "Guiana Amazonian Park" for French Guiana's protected rainforest area.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] The Amazon represents over half of the total area of remaining rainforests on Earth, and comprises the largest and most biodiverse tract of tropical rainforest in the world, with an estimated 390 billion individual trees in about 16,000 species.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] More than 30 million people of 350 different ethnic groups live in the Amazon, which are subdivided into 9 different national political systems and 3,344 formally acknowledged indigenous territories.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] Indigenous peoples make up 9% of the total population, and 60 groups remain largely isolated.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] Large scale deforestation is occurring in the forest, creating different harmful effects.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] Economic losses due to deforestation in Brazil could be approximately 7 times higher in comparison to the cost of all commodities produced through deforestation.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] In 2023, the World Bank published a report proposing a non-deforestation based economic program in the region.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] The name *Amazon* is said to arise from a war Francisco de Orellana fought with the Tapuyas and other tribes.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] The women of the tribe fought alongside the men, as was their custom.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] Orellana derived the name *Amazonas* from the Amazons of Greek mythology, described by Herodotus and Diodorus.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] Based on archaeological evidence from an excavation at Caverna da Pedra Pintada, human inhabitants first settled in the Amazon region at least 11,200 years ago.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] Subsequent development led to late-prehistoric settlements along the periphery of the forest by AD 1250, which induced alterations in the forest cover.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] For a long time, it was thought that the Amazon rainforest was never more than sparsely populated, as it was impossible to sustain a large population through agriculture given the poor soil.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] Archeologist Betty Meggers was a prominent proponent of this idea, as described in her book *Amazonia: Man and Culture in a Counterfeit Paradise*.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] She claimed that a population density of 0.2 inhabitants per square kilometre (0.52/sq mi) is the maximum that can be sustained in the rainforest through hunting, with agriculture needed to host a larger population.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] However, recent anthropological findings have suggested that the region was actually densely populated.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] The Upano Valley sites in present-day eastern Ecuador predate all known complex Amazonian societies.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] Some 5 million people may have lived in the Amazon region in AD 1500, divided between dense coastal settlements, such as that at Marajó, and inland dwellers.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] Based on projections of food production, one estimate suggests over 8 million people living in the Amazon in 1492.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] By 1900, the native indigenous population had fallen to 1 million and by the early 1980s it was less than 200,000.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] The first European to travel the length of the Amazon River was Francisco de Orellana in 1542.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] The BBC's *Unnatural Histories* presents evidence that Orellana, rather than exaggerating his claims as previously thought, was correct in his observations that a complex civilization was flourishing along the Amazon in the 1540s.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] The Pre-Columbian agriculture in the Amazon Basin was sufficiently advanced to support prosperous and populous societies.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] It is believed that civilization was later devastated by the spread of diseases from Europe, such as smallpox.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] This civilization was investigated by the British explorer Percy Fawcett in the early twentieth century.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] The results of his expeditions were inconclusive, and he disappeared mysteriously on his last trip.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] His name for this lost civilization was the City of Z.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] Since the 1970s, numerous geoglyphs have been discovered on deforested land dating between AD 1–1250, furthering claims about Pre-Columbian civilizations.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] Ondemar Dias is accredited with first discovering the geoglyphs in 1977, and Alceu Ranzi is credited with furthering their discovery after flying over Acre.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] The BBC's *Unnatural Histories* presented evidence that the Amazon rainforest, rather than being a pristine wilderness, has been shaped by man for at least 11,000 years through practices such as forest gardening and *terra preta*.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] Terra preta is found over large areas in the Amazon forest; and is now widely accepted as a product of indigenous soil management.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] The development of this fertile soil allowed agriculture and silviculture in the previously hostile environment; meaning that large portions of the Amazon rainforest are probably the result of centuries of human management, rather than naturally occurring as has previously been supposed.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] In the region of the Xingu tribe, remains of some of these large settlements in the middle of the Amazon forest were found in 2003 by Michael Heckenberger and colleagues of the University of Florida.
[src:amazon-rainforest/amazon-rainforest] Among those were evidence of roads, bridges and large plazas.
